<TEXT>
the federal filed suit thursday against the 
state of nevada claiming the state is acting illegally in refusing 
to issue environmental permits for work on the proposed nuclear 
dump at yucca mountain 
the us district court suit also asks that legislative 
resolutions and a state law banning the dump be declared invalid 
because they are preempted by a congressional directive to conduct 
scientific studies of the site 
state officials have adamantly opposed any plans for work at 
yucca mountain which congress picked in late 1987 as the nations 
only site to be studied for a highlevel radioactive waste dump it 
would be used to store spent fuel rods from commercial nuclear 
reactors 
the department of energy said in november it planned to file the 
suit the action asks a judge to order state officials to issue the 
necessary permits within 30 days and prohibit the state from 
unlawfully interfering with the does activities at the site 
we have tried to work with the state over the years but 
unfortunately they have refused to cooperate in that area said 
carl gertz the nuclear dump project director we were forced 
into filing this suit so we can move ahead with scientific 
studies 
the department of justice suit was seen as unusual by attorneys 
who said it was rare that the federal government would sue a state 
for trying to block federal law 
usually its the other way around said doe attorney dave 
gassman but the federal program must prevail it is a very basic 
issue 
in december the state attorney generals office filed suit 
claiming the state has the right to bar the doe from following 
congresss mandate because the nevada legislature has passed 
resolutions disapproving the yucca mountain site 
the state contends it has the right under the federal 
legislation to veto the site and is also bound by a law passed by 
the 1989 legislature that makes it illegal to put a nuclear waste 
dump in nevada 
the 21page suit filed in us district court in las vegas is 
seen by doe officials as the only way to get the much delayed 
project back on track 
in november the agency announced it was revamping its schedule 
for the controversial facility and would open it in the year 2010 
seven years later than planned 
gertz said the doe needs to get the state permits and begin 
exploratory drilling and other scientific work at the site by next 
january to even be able to keep current with the revised schedule 
state officials in december returned the air and water permits 
to the doe unprocessed saying state law precluded them from 
granting permits to build the dump the doe originally applied for 
the permits in january 1988 
</TEXT>
