<TEXT>
the czechoslovakian aviation industry and 
general electric co announced an agreement wednesday to produce a 
40passenger commuter airplane 
under the joint venture the engines of the ct79b powered 
versions of l610 turboprop plane will be manufactured in ge 
aircraft engines plant here the aircraft will be built by the 
stateowned czechoslovakian company which is known in that country 
by the acronym let 
about 400 engines will be supplied for the plane which will be 
marketed around the world by let said robert n salvucci manager 
of media relations for ge aircraft engines 
salvucci said the deal marked the first time a western nation 
would sell an aircraft engine to an eastern bloc nation for use in 
a commercial venture czechoslovakia like other eastern european 
countries has undergone dramatic political liberalization in 
recent months 
this agreement will allow both parties to serve markets in 
parts of the world that have not previously been accessible said 
wallie everest director of ges ct7 turboprop program in a 
statement released by the company 
we expect that well over 300 million worth of ct7 engines 
will be purchased by the late 1990s and spare parts sales will add 
to that business he said 
czechoslovakian aeronautics industry and ge aircraft engines 
also have agreed to develop a longterm relationship that will 
include the manufacture of selected ge aircraft engine components 
by let and other czech factories 
this program will be a major step in the development of 
worldwide commerce for both of our companies said frantisek 
hava general director of omnipol a czechoslovakian aviation 
company 
ges ct7 turboprop engines were first used in commercial flights 
in june 1984 and now power more than 190 aircraft in 16 countries 
</TEXT>
