<TEXT>
police staged nationwide raids on the 
homes of dozens of suspected neonazis and confiscated reams of 
rightwing extremist propaganda officials said 
west german police raided 40 residences in 26 cities on 
wednesday in a coordinated move to confiscate neonazi material 
according to a statement by state police in stuttgart 
about 200 police officiers took part in the raids which 
targeted suspected members of the action front national 
socialistsnational activists 
the group officially banned in 1986 as a threat to the 
constitution was founded by former west germany army lt michael 
kuehnen in the 1970s police say the group has between 800 and 
1000 active members 
kuehnen a selfproclaimed successor to adolf hitler has been 
jailed several times over the past decade for extremerightist 
activities including incitement of the public and publicly 
preaching nazi propaganda 
he is currently free 
included in the confiscated matter was training material to 
indoctrinate new members along with neonazi advertising 
propaganda the statement said 
among the cities where the raids were staged were west berlin 
hamburg cologne essen and aachen police said 
no one was arrested during the searches but police said arrests 
were possible after officials have evaluated the confiscated 
material 
similar searches in west germany were carried out against 
neonazis in 1988 resulting in charges against five people for 
membership in a banned extremist organization 
