<TEXT>
women who give up smoking lower their risk of 
heart attacks quickly just as men do a study today concludes 
women who smoke face nearly four times the usual risk of heart 
attacks before age 65 earlier research has shown that the high 
risk of heart attacks in male smokers goes away within a few years 
of stopping but the new study is the first to show that this also 
happens in women 
the present data underscore the value of smoking cessation for 
women as for men and may give women a convincing motive to quit 
even if they have smoked heavily for many years the researchers 
wrote in the new england journal of medicine 
the study found that the risk of suffering a first heart attack 
was 36 times higher among current smokers than among those who 
never had smoked however within three years of giving up smoking 
their risk had dropped to the point where it was no higher than 
that of the nonsmokers 
smoking has fallen from favor among both sexes although the 
decline has been steeper among men during the past two decades 
the proportion of men who smoke has fallen from 51 percent to 29 
percent while among women it has dropped from 33 percent to 24 
percent 
the latest analysis was conducted by dr lynn rosenberg and 
colleagues from the sloan epidemiology unit at boston university 
school of medicine 
the work was based on 910 women who were admitted for heart 
attacks at 71 hospitals in massachusetts rhode island connecticut 
and new york their smoking habits were compared to those of 2375 
women who were in the hospitals for other reasons 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

