clan from which a northern insurgent group the somali national 
movement largely draws its strength 
amnesty noted that it had been allowed to send a delegation to 
somalia in june for the first time in 20 years but said it 
received few replies from the government since then 
shortly after its june visit amnesty said there were new 
arrests of suspected political opponents killings of demonstrators 
and extrajudicial executions the organization said most 
political prisoners are held under a vague security law and tried 
by a court lacking judicial independence 
amnesty said defendants can be sentenced to death for 
organizing a subversive association or strikes and exploiting 
religion for creating national disunity 
washington has withheld or canceled more than 50 million in aid 
dating back to 1987 because of human rights abuses britain france 
and other western donors also have slashed funds 
siad barre a major general said to be in his 80s seized power 
in october 1968 to prevent the election to the presidency of a 
civilian opposed by the army in recent years he has ruled a 
deteriorating nation beset by tribal rebellions in the north and 
south clan warfare and a bankrupt economy 
somalia became independent in 1960 after the unification of the 
