<TEXT>
a generation of us military officers reared 
on the threat of a soviet invasion of europe now agree the warsaw 
pact is dying in the wake of the revolution in eastern europe 
but some regard the demise of their old enemy as a mixed 
blessing 
these changes in eastern europe reduce the soviet unions 
confidence and capacity to wage coalition warfare said lt gen 
henry soyster head of the pentagons defense intelligence agency 
an organization that historically has emphasized soviet strengths 
rather than weaknesses 
soviet officials have not publicly acknowledged the de facto 
collapse of their alliance declaring instead their readiness to 
transform the warsaw pact from a military into a political 
organization 
us analysts say such a transformation has little chance of 
success 
for the united states and its 15 allies in the north atlantic 
treaty organization the collapse of their eastern counterpart 
creates some uneasiness 
at the height of the east european revolution last fall many 
us officials thought the warsaw pact should be preserved as a 
vehicle for negotiating conventional force reductions in europe and 
as a forum for resolving potential disagreements within the soviet 
bloc said one administration source 
most policymakers now have concluded that there is a danger in 
the artificial perpetuation of an institution that might collapse 
of its own weight said the source who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
dissenters from that view want a warsaw pact because of the 
shaken confidence which would result from a sudden demise the 
source said 
soyster said the collapse of the warsaw pact virtually 
eliminated the threat of an eastwest confrontation in europe 
which for decades was deemed the most likely starting place for a 
superpower war 
i believe that the soviets would consider large scale theater 
operations against nato with only their own forces as highly risky 
if not impractical soyster testified on the first day of senate 
armed service committee hearings on the soviet threat 
at a conference of eastern and western military officers last 
week in vienna lt gen nikolai chervov of the soviet general 
staff said there will be major restructuring of the eastern 
blocs military command apparatus handing authority from soviet 
generals to east european elected leaders soyster told the senate 
committee 
the point chervov and others soviets have said is to transform 
the warsaw pact from a military into a political organization 
the warsaw pact is dead as a military organization because 
the eastern european nations are asking the soviets to withdraw 
their troops how can they expect to keep it as a political 
