<DOCNO> AP900125-0026 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a panel of experts says the government must 
do more to turn down the volume in the workplace and on consumer 
products to save the hearing of millions of americans 
the panel convened by the national institutes of health on 
wednesday concluded that better protection for workers noise 
labeling of consumer products limits on noise levels for some 
products and an educational campaign would cut the number of people 
with hearing problems 
of the 28 million americans who suffer hearing loss about 10 
million of the impairments were caused at least partly by exposure 
to loud noises the panel said 
dr patrick e brookhouser panel chairman and director of the 
boys town national research hospital in omaha neb said although 
the united states is the world leader in hearingloss research 
the fact that were not continuing to implement our own 
recommendations is a concern to the panel 
we know how to solve the problem we just dont want to put in 
the effort and expense for it he said 
unnecessary hearing loss is occurring now because were not 
implementing what we already know are good preventive strategies 
exposure to loud sounds in the workplace is the most common 
cause of noiserelated hearing loss and poses a danger to 
firefighters police officers military personnel construction and 
factory workers musicians farmers and truck drivers among 
others the panel said 
outside the workplace hazards include loud music recreational 
vehicles airplanes lawncare equipment woodworking tools some 
household appliances and chain saws the panel said 
short bursts of loud noise as in an explosion or gunfire can 
damage hearing permanently while longer exposure to less intense 
but still loud noise exacts a gradual toll on hearing 
sensitivity initially without the victims awareness the panel 
said in a statement 
hearing loss is irreversible when the sensitive innerear 
structure is damaged said brookhouser 
one of the problems is that people are losing hearing and they 
dont know it because its not painful he said 
exposure to sounds up to 75 decibels which is the noise of a 
dishwasher or vacuum cleaner are generally safe even over long 
periods of exposure he said 
however sounds at levels more than 85 decibels which is the 
noise level of a lawnmower or food blender for eight hours a day 
over a long period of time can damage hearing permanently he said 
the greater the noise the shorter the period of exposure necessary 
to cause permanent damage 
two warning signs of dangerous noise exposure are ringing in the 
ears and a muffling of sounds that are heard 
a rock concert delivers about 130 decibels of sound which can 
cause a temporary hearing loss that can take several days or a week 
to recover from brookhouser said 
he noted some in the concert industry have begun voluntarily to 
lower the volume because they are becoming more aware of the 
dangers to hearing 
panel members called for more such efforts in the entertainment 
field and for manufacturers to design quieter products and 
regulations to limit the maximum noise of certain products such as 
portable cassette players 
the panel also called for reestablishment of the environmental 
protection agencys office of noise abatement and control which 
was closed during the reagan administration in 1982 
julia doswell royster president of environmental noise 
consultants inc in cary nc said existing epa noise rules are 
largely unenforced the occupational health and safety 
administration also has regulations covering workers but she said 
they should be stronger and better enforced 
epa spokesman dave ryan said the agency has taken no enforcement 
actions since the office closed but is conducting five compliance 
investigations of makers of hearing protectors 
</TEXT>
