four suspected members of the irish 
republican army are charged by a grand jury with violating the us 
neutrality act by conspiring to ship weapons including a stinger 
missile to northern ireland 
the fivecount federal indictment wednesday also accused the men 
of violating the us arms export control act which requires arms 
dealers to get permission from the state department before shipping 
weapons overseas 
department policy is to deny permission when the weapons are 
intended for use in connection with the sectarian conflict in 
northern ireland the indictment said this is in keeping with 
united states policy to encourage peaceful reconciliation in 
northern ireland 
other weapons the indictment accuses the men of conspiring to 
ship to northern ireland include rifles grenade launchers and 
plastic explosives 
indictment are kevin joseph mckinley 33 of riviera beach sean 
mccann 34 of toronto seamus anthony moley 30 of canada and 
joseph martin mccolgan 39 of dundalk northern ireland each 
faces a maximum penalty of 38 years in prison 
us magistrate ann vitunac ordered the men held until trial 
arraignment is set for friday 
arms dealers are required to be licensed by the us office of 
munitions control before shipping weapons abroad exporters must 
tell the federal agency what weapons they wish to ship and to whom 
the indictment states 
at no time did the defendants apply for receive or possess 
a license to export defense articles of any description the 
indictment charges 
the indictment details a series of meetings between the men and 
two undercover agents from the us customs service and the bureau 
of alcohol tobacco and firearms 
the meetings culminated at a west palm beach warehouse jan 12 
when the two undercover agents allowed mccolgan to inspect the 
stinger missile and place it in the back seat of his car agents 
said the four men were arrested soon after the missile was 
delivered 
