<DOCNO> AP900125-0048 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
discovery of a genetic defect that apparently 
causes one kind of retinitis pigmentosa may help researchers find 
defects that cause other forms of the visionrobbing disease 
scientists said 
study of genetic defects may reveal leads for devising 
treatments for the inherited condition they added 
retinitis pigmentosa which afflicts about 100000 americans 
gradually progresses from night blindness to tunnel vision to 
blindness symptoms are caused by degeneration of the retina a 
delicate layer of cells at the back of the eye that detects images 
and relays them to the brain 
the newly discovered defect apparently keeps the eye from 
producing a fully functional version of an important protein 
researchers said 
the new work is reported in todays issue of the british journal 
nature by eliot berson thaddeus dryja and colleagues at the 
massachusetts eye and ear infirmary in boston 
it focuses on the autosomal dominant form of retinitis 
pigmentosa which accounts for perhaps 43000 cases in the united 
states said jeanette felix director of science for the 
baltimorebased rp foundation fighting blindness 
the genetic defect the researchers found may be responsible for 
about 5000 of those cases she said but the studys impact may go 
beyond that because it focuses attention on a particular gene and 
further work may turn up more defects in that gene that cause other 
forms of the disease she said 
in addition the researchers wrote the finding suggests that 
other genes that play similar roles in the eye should be studied 
for defects that cause other forms of retinitis pigmentosa 
the researchers studied the gene that tells eye cells how to 
make a protein called rhodopsin this lightsensing substance plays 
a major role in vision during twilight and it is found in the 
rod cells of the eyes the first to die in retinitis pigmentosa 
the defect appeared in rhodopsin genes from 17 of 148 unrelated 
patients with retinitis pigmentosa but not in any of 102 people 
without the disease the researchers reported 
it is unclear how the defect causes the disease they said 
scientists must answer that question by introducing the 
defective gene into experimental animals and studying the result 
felix said once the answer is found it may lead to experiments to 
find ways to block the disease process she said 
currently scientists do not know how to stop the progression of 
the disease she said 
the new finding allows specific diagnosis of one form of 
retinitis pigmentosa and accurate genetic counseling for those who 
have the genetic defect said meredithe applebury of the university 
of chicago 
such people have a 50 percent chance of passing the 
diseasecausing defect on to their children she said in an 
editorial accompanying the report in nature 
</TEXT>
