<TEXT>
china today strongly condemned a vote in the 
house of representatives to protect chinese students in the united 
states and said passage of the legislation would do serious 
harm to uschinese relations 
the house voted 39025 wednesday to override president bushs 
veto of legislation that would allow chinese students many of whom 
face possible political persecution at home to overstay their us 
visas 
foreign ministry spokesman jin guihua said the house had based 
its policy on rumors fully revealing its antichina position 
we express great indignation and strongly condemn this 
hegemonist act of the us house of representatives jin told a 
weekly briefing 
should the us senate also adopt such a bill it would 
certainly do serious harm to sinous relations and further impair 
the cultural and educational exchanges between the two countries 
the legislation applies to some 32000 chinese students many of 
whom openly criticized the chinese government after its bloody 
suppression of the prodemocracy movement last spring 
the senate was to vote on the bill today and bush was pressing 
republican senators to oppose the veto override which needs a 
twothirds vote of both chambers to pass 
bush who says it is important to maintain channels of contact 
with the chinese leadership has initiated administrative measures 
that provide chinese students similar guarantees against forced 
deportation 
jin did not say how the chinese might retaliate if the student 
bill becomes law warning only that the united states must take 
prompt and effective measures to prevent the deterioration of the 
situation 
nearly half of all chinese students abroad are in the united 
states and any chinese decision to curtail exchange programs would 
affect thousands of students in china applying for overseas studies 
jin said congress was trying to obstruct students from returning 
for service in their home country and accused us lawmakers of 
supporting the reactionary front for democracy in china and the 
chinese democratc alliance 
the two groups based in paris and new york are operated by 
prodemocracy chinese exiles the front was organized by dissidents 
who fled the country after the june military crackdown on the 
prodemocracy movement in which hundreds of unarmed civilians were 
killed 
jin also took a hardline stance on two other dissidents 
astrophysicist fang lizhi and his wife li shuxian who have been 
given refuge in the us embassy in beijing since june 
jin said the two are criminals wanted by chinas security 
organs and that the united states was breaking international law 
by harboring them 
his statements echoed the stance china had taken before us 
national security adviser brent scowcroft visited beijing in 
december that vsiit appeared to set the two countries on a course 
of improved relations 
