<TEXT>
a consumer group began a campaign against 
disposable products today urging environmentally concerned 
shoppers to telephone their displeasure to manufacturers tollfree 
consumer lines 
the new york public interest research group published a guide to 
what it said were the worst examples of disposable overpackaged 
and nonrecyclable consumer products that deplete resources and jam 
landfills 
although it did not call for a boycott the group urged 
consumers to complain about items such as disposable diapers and 
razors plastic utensils polystyrene foam packages and socalled 
degradable plastic bags 
given the garbage disposal crisis across much of the country 
consumers need to send these companies a clear message that they 
dont want and dont need these socalled convenience items and 
overpackaged products steven a romalewski the guides author 
said in an interview 
the guide singled out a few items as examples of the worst in 
throwaway packaging including eastman kodak cos fling 
disposable camera quaker oats cos aunt jemima pancake 
express which has mix for six pancakes in a disposable plastic 
mixing bowl and heinz usas plastic ketchup bottles 
the ketchup bottles are difficult to recycle because they are 
made of laminated layers of plastics the guide said 
juiceinabox containers used by more than a halfdozen fruit 
drink producers pose the same problem because they contain layered 
plastic aluminium foil and paper it said 
while degradable plastic bags have been promoted as a 
partial solution to the landfill crisis the guide cited complaints 
from environmental groups that the bags only break down into 
smaller plastic particles which remain in the environment 
it also said they may not break down when buried and could 
weaken products made from recycled plastic 
especially at a time when industries are trying to cash in on 
the green decade and this new environmentalism they cant just try 
to give the appearance that theyre doing good for the 
environment romalewski said they have to take some tough 
action 
heinz spokeswoman beth adams however said her company was 
between a rock and a hard place because consumers prefer 
plastic bottles and only the nonrecyclable kind are airproof 
enough to keep ketchup from darkening 
she said heinz in pittsburgh continues to sell glass bottles 
though they now make up only about 35 percent of its bottled 
ketchup sales and is searching fast and furious for a 
recyclable plastic bottle it can use 
at kodak in rochester ny spokeswoman holly walkland read a 
letter prepared for customers who complain about the fling 
camera maintaining that it does not contain significantly more 
material than some film cartridges 
quaker oats spokesman ron bottrell in chicago had no comment 
romalewski said boycotts seldom work unless targeted at a 
specific product but the public interest group hopes to make its 
point by listing the telephone numbers of nearly two dozen 
companies whose products it criticized and urging consumers to 
call 
the 20page guide is being distributed to consumer and 
environmental groups across the country copies are available for 
3 from nypirg 9 murray st ny ny 10007 212 3496460 
