washington 
the agency with 16000 employees and an annual budget of more 
than 5 billion would become the 15th cabinetlevel department 
the cabinet was last expanded in 1988 when the department of 
veterans affairs was added 
congressional and administration sources said the proposal 
before congress would not change the agency significantly in 
structure or size one exception would be creation of a bureau of 
environmental statistics to keep tabs on environmental data 
but elevation to cabinet secretary would give the epa 
administrator more clout within the government and increased 
prestige in dealings with other countries say environmentalists 
and congressional supporters of the change although reilly attends 
many cabinet meetings he does not as a routine sit at the table 
its a different dynamic to have a seat at the table said 
frederick krupp executive director of the environmental defense 
fund finally we would have a secretary of the environment who 
can bring things up at cabinet meeting as well as react to the 
harebrained ideas of the secretary of defense or whoever 
but michael fischer executive director of the sierra club 
cautioned elevating the epa to the cabinet is no substitute for 
the president himself being a leader for strong environmental 
legislation and worldwide environmental negotiations 
