<TEXT>
a foreign ministry spokesman confirmed today that 
foreign correspondents based in beijing no longer will have to 
apply 10 days in advance to cover events outside the capital 
spokesman jin guihua however made clear at a news briefing 
that under new regulations announced saturday foreign reporters 
still need permission from local authorities for all trips outside 
beijing 
consequently local officials still have the authority to bar 
foreign reporters from covering demonstrations natural disasters 
or other breaking events 
the 10day rule was imposed in 1986 but generally ignored until 
october 1987 when authorities in the tibetan capital lhasa 
invoked it to expel foreign reporters who had gone there to cover 
antichinese riots 
lhasa has been under martial law since march and with rare 
exceptions all applications by journalists to visit the city have 
been rejected 
jin said the ministry had taken into consideration the views 
put forward by foreign journalists in the past concerning the 
10day rule and that the new regulations omitted the rule to 
facilitate the press coverage in china by foreign journalists 
he stressed that the regulations require all foreign journalists 
to obtain permission from local foreign affairs offices before 
leaving beijing for reporting in other parts of the country 
asked about clauses in the new regulations saying journalists 
may lose their accreditation if they distort the facts create 
rumors or use improper methods to interview or report jin urged 
journalists to follow the regulations 
foreign correspondents need not worry so long as they abide by 
the regulations and observe their professional ethics and make 
legitimate press coverage in china he said the chinese 
government has all along dealt with cases according to facts and 
according to law 
after the suppression of prodemocracy protests in june chinese 
authorities expelled two american journalists who had been based in 
beijing and ordered half a dozen reporters who had come from 
outside china to cover the political turmoil to leave the country 
the journalists were accused of violating martial law 
regulations on news coverage under martial law which was lifted 
in beijing earlier this month all interviews had to be approved by 
military authorities 
