<TEXT>
two researchers havent come up with a cure for 
the common cold but they think theyve discovered a link to the 
cause of another common ailment flu 
they blame an overactive sun marked by a peak in its sunspot 
activity 
the solar connection was proposed in a letter to the editor in 
todays issue of the british journal nature by astronomer sir fred 
hoyle and his colleague nc wickramasinghe 
but an influenza researcher says he doubts that flu outbreaks 
are linked to solar activity 
there are many other attractive theories about what causes 
influenza outbreaks so i dont think we have to hypothesize that 
they come raining down from the atmosphere said paul glezen of 
the baylor college of medicine 
sunspots are dark markings that show up periodically on the sun 
on average the number of sunspots peaks every 11 years or so 
the analysis of the british researchers suggests that peak 
sunspot activity and flu pandemics have occurred at about the same 
time unusually often from 1761 to 1893 and from 1919 to 1979 
solar activity peaks when the number of sunspots is at a 
maximum the british researchers said 
electrical fields associated with intense solar winds can 
rapidly drive charged particles of the size of viruses down through 
the exposed upper atmosphere into the shelter of the lower 
atmosphere possibly causing the link to influenza they wrote 
but glezen an epidemiologist at baylors influenza research 
center said the idea doesnt sound too likely 
influenza viruses have a fatty covering that is not very stable 
outside the body so it is hard to imagine that a virus particle 
could be floating around for a very long time in the atmosphere and 
remain viable he said 
</TEXT>
