<TEXT>
parliament passed a law today that 
limits the powers of the secret police the new restrictions came 
in response to reports that security services routinely spied on 
legal opposition parties 
the legislation stipulates that covert intelligence gathering 
will be permitted only when the security of the nation the 
sovereignty of the country and its constitutional order are 
endangered by secret activities 
the vote was 279 for none against and 14 abstentions 
also two government officials interior minister state 
secretary zoltan gal and justice minister kalman kulcsar were 
given responsibility for intelligence operations 
introducing the bill entitled temporary regulation of the use 
of special secret service methods and means gal told parliament 
on wednesday that intelligence agencies had had little past 
supervision when hungary was a oneparty communist state 
the interim legislation was hurriedly introduced following a 
national uproar over revelations that the state security service 
was spying on scores of people including some members of 
parliament gal said a permanent and comprehensive bill governing 
the activities of the security services will be presented in 
parliament in february 
the scandal broke jan 5 when representatives of two opposition 
organizations presented reporters with secret documents leaked to 
them by a member of the secret police 
secret police targets of intelligence gathering included 
opposition parties and personalities writers and religious 
figures according to the documents 
chief public prosecutor karoly szijarto disclosed wednesday that 
the illegal eavesdropping was even more widespread than originally 
thought 
szijarto told the legislature the internal security department 
of the interior ministry even spied on the socialist party its 
predecessor the socialist workers party and other communist or 
leftist organizations the investigation is still under way 
while claiming to have had no knowledge of such practices 
interior minister istvan horvath resigned tuesday telling 
legislators that in a democracy that is the custom 
hungary formally became a multiparty state oct 23 and the 
first free elections since 1948 are scheduled for march 25 
although the socialist party asserts it was uninvolved the scandal 
is believed to have hurt its chances at the polls because it 
happened under its tenure 
the hungarian democratic forum the biggest opposition party 
already has signaled its opposition to the idea of a future 
coalition with the socialists in a clear indication of the partys 
desire to distance itself from what it considers a political 
liability 
the interim law also changed the name of the main intelligence 
agency from the state security service to national security service 
