<TEXT>
a democratic westernstyle 
constitution was formally presented thursday to the constituent 
assembly which is expected to approve the document and set a date 
for independence probably in march 
unlike most constitutions in africa the document sets a limit 
of two fiveyear terms for the president who is to be chosen 
through national elections however to avoid the need for an 
immediate election the first president will be chosen by 
parliament 
the constitution also says parliament can impeach the president 
by a twothirds vote it prohibits capital punishment 
the first president is expected to be sam nujoma leader of the 
southwest africa peoples organization swapo waged a 23year 
guerrilla war against south african rule that ended in april 
south africa has ruled namibia for 75 years but has agreed to 
grant independence to the semidesert territory under united nations 
supervision 
hage geingob a swapo official who is chairman of the 
constituent assembly said the committee that wrote the 
constitution was inspired by a spirit of reconciliation brother 
and sisterhood and commitment to the future of this great 
country 
all seven political parties that captured seats in novembers 
elections took part in writing the constitution 
the full assembly took no immediate action on the document but 
is expected to do so when it meets again on monday 
the document has a declaration of fundamental rights including 
freedom of movement speech and a free press it also envisions a 
multiparty democracy regular elections an independent judiciary 
and an executive president 
leftistoriented swapo captured 41 of the 72 seats in the 
constituent assembly during elections in november but at least 48 
or twothirds of the assembly members must approve the 
constitution 
the democratic turnhalle alliance a multiracial coalition that 
favors a capitalist economy has 21 seats the remaining 10 seats 
are divided among five other parties 
despite a hardfought campaign and major ideological 
differences the assembly quickly worked out compromises on the 
constitution after beginnning work in november 
the more than 6000 un military and civilian personnel in 
namibia are scheduled to remain until the end of march the head of 
the un contingent martti ahtisaari has said he expects namibia 
to attain independence before the un forces leave 
under the proposed constitution the constituent assembly will 
be converted into the national assembly which will be the dominant 
chamber of parliament and have legislative powers 
a second chamber the national council will consist of members 
elected on a regional basis it will be empowered to review 
legislation and to refer bills back to the assembly but it cannot 
kill bills the assembly approves again 
