<TEXT>
a consumer group mounted a complaint campaign 
thursday against manufacturers of disposable and nonrecyclable 
products charging that wasteful packaging depletes resources and 
jams the nations landfills 
the new york public interest research group published a 20page 
guide to what it called the worst of environmentally damaging 
packaging listing tollfree telephone numbers of the products 
makers and urging calls of complaint 
consumers need to send these companies a clear message that 
they dont want and dont need these socalled convenience items 
and overpackaged products steven a romalewski author of the 
guide said in an interview 
some of the guides examples are familiar targets of 
environmentalist criticism including disposable diapers 
disposable razors plastic utensils polystyrene foam packages and 
socalled degradable plastic bags 
it also faults specialized convenience products such as eastman 
kodak cos fling disposable camera quaker oats cos aunt jemima 
pancake express with mix for six pancakes and a throwaway plastic 
mixing bowl and heinz usas plastic ketchup bottles 
the ketchup bottles are nonrecyclable because they are made of 
laminated plastic layers that cannot be separated easily juice 
boxes used by more than a halfdozen fruit drink producers pose the 
same problem because they contain layered plastic aluminium foil 
and paper 
while degradable plastic bags have been promoted as a 
partial solution to the landfill crisis the guide cited complaints 
from environmental groups that the bags only break down into 
smaller plastic particles which remain in the environment it also 
said they may not break down when buried and could weaken products 
made from recycled plastic 
in interviews spokesmen for some of the companies criticized by 
nypirg protested that they were squeezed by conflicting 
environmental concerns on one side and consumer preferences on the 
other 
were between a rock and a hard place said heinz 
spokeswoman beth adams because consumers prefer plastic bottles 
and only laminated plastic is airproof enough to keep ketchup from 
darkening 
she said heinz in pittsburgh continues to sell glass bottles 
but they now make up only about 35 percent of its bottled ketchup 
sales the company is searching fast and furious for a 
recyclable plastic bottle she said 
ron bottrell at quaker oats in chicago made a similar argument 
for pancake express saying the company had to balance 
conflicting concerns of environmentalists and of most shoppers 
while environment groups want biodegradable packaging 
consumers are telling us with their dollars that convenience is 
the driving force in their purchasing habits he said the food 
company is in the middle 
at kodak in rochester spokeswoman holly walkland read a letter 
prepared for customers who complain about the fling camera 
maintaining that it does not contain much more material than a 
dropin 110 film cartridge the letter also said photofinishers 
dispose of the camera in a manner prescribed by local 
ordinances 
walkland added that kodak was actively exploring not just for 
singleuse cameras but for all of our products how they can be 
recycled 
nypirgs romalewski said such promises were not enough for his 
group 
especially at a time when industries are trying to cash in on 
the green decade and this new environmentalism they cant just try 
to give the appearance that theyre doing good for the 
environment he said they have to take some tough action 
his group decided against boycotts because it believes they work 
only when targeted at a single product romalewski said he said 
nypirg instead hoped to make its point by inspiring complaint calls 
to the nearly two dozen companies whose products it criticized 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the guide is being distributed to consumer and 
environmental groups and are available for 3 from nypirg 9 murray 
st new york ny 10007 212 3496460 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

