<TEXT>
president bush today proposed a 11 billion 
increase in federal spending for the war on drugs and said he was 
committed to marshaling everything that works to combat what he 
called the nations no 1 concern 
bushs 106 billion plan designates five regions new york 
los angeles miami houston and the southwest border of california 
arizona new mexico and texas as highintensity drug trafficking 
areas eligible for millions of dollars in additional federal help 
this year and next 
we want to help them map out a more comprehensive coordinated 
approach to fight drugs the president said in a luncheon speech 
to about 75 newspaper publishers 
he said his administration has made progress in battling drugs 
in the four months since he unveiled an action plan but added 
given the headlines weve seen recently its clear were only 
getting started 
he also called on congress to broaden the definition of 
drugrelated crimes for which the death penalty may be applied 
the budget proposal would spend 42 percent of the money for 
domestic law enforcement 29 percent for border interdiction and 
international operations and 29 percent for demand reduction said 
john walters chief of staff to drug policy director william j 
bennett 
to those who say our program looks topheavy on the 
interdiction side remember that many of the efforts to limit 
supply are exclusively federal and inherently more expensive than 
demand reduction bush said 
were willing to spend more to limit the drug supply simply 
put were willing to do whatever it takes 
bush made the comments as he unveiled what he called a 
blueprint for success a series of proposals that build upon the 
national drug strategy he announced last sept 5 
were committed to the same aggressive goals and principles we 
outlined last september to reduce use through an integrated mix 
of supply and demandside approaches and that means doing 
everything that works bush said 
he said illegal drugs remain this nations no 1 concern 
the president reiterated his earlier call for the death penalty 
for convicted drug kingpins responsible for drugrelated 
killings and he said even in some cases attempted killings 
we want there to be absolutely no doubt about the certainty of 
punishment bush said 
the proposal calls for allowing the death penalty for drug 
kingpins even when they or their organizations have not killed 
anyone for drug kingpins who attempt to kill in order to obstruct 
justice and for federal drug felons whose offenses result in 
death such as a drug users overdose 
bush also praised efforts by the leaders of mexico and colombia 
in fighting drug traffickers in their countries said said he would 
reinforce our support for the courageous leaders of the region 
at the upcoming feb 15 drug summit in colombia 
bush vowed to do what it takes to see drug operations 
dismantled and destroyed 
we dont make deals with dealers he said 
asked about arguments in favor of drug legalization bush said 
i just think that it would increase regrettably the habit and i 
strongly oppose it im just going to hold the line against 
legalization 
the updated strategy developed by policy director bennett 
emphasizes the crucial role of state and local governments to 
that end it calls for 26 billion in 1991 to be sent to the 
states for law enforcement treatment and drug prevention efforts 
a 108 percent increase over the past two years 
last september bush sought 79 billion for the war against 
drugs in 1990 but congress increased that to 88 billion the 
current proposal also is subject to congressional approval 
although 88 billion has been the universally recognized figure 
for the 1990 budget the new strategy uses new figures that take 
into account other drug expenditures already being made and says 
the country is now spending 95 billion walters said 
overall criminal justice spending will increase 2 percent to 
43 billion treatment goes up 12 percent to 15 billion 
educationcommunity and workplace funding goes up 11 percent to 
12 billion 
also international initiatives shoot up 65 percent to 690 
million interdiction efforts increase 17 percent to 24 billion 
research hikes 20 percent to 383 million and intelligence efforts 
zoom up 142 percent to 172 million 
meanwhile sen joseph r biden jr ddel told the national 
conference of mayors that the administration has placed too much 
emphasis on casual users and not enough on hardcore addicts 
its not that the administration doesnt care about hardcore 
users they do the judiciary committee chairman said as he 
touted his rival 146 billion antidrug strategy but that is 
not their main emphasis 
bennett told reporters earlier that the administrations plan 
was in 90 percent agreement with bidens and he wouldnt 
oppose it if congress decides to add more money for 1991 as it did 
for 1990 i could spend any amount of money on this he said 
the pentagon long reluctant to enter the drug war will 
contribute about 12 billion in 1991 with about 638 million of 
that going for detection and monitoring of traffickers trying to 
enter the country with illicit drugs according to the new 
strategy its efforts this year total 878 million 
bruce carnes bennetts budget specialist said the military 
drug war budget for 1991 represents the biggest dollar increase 
proposed in the strategy 
it is followed by the department of health and human services 
alcohol drug abuse and mental health administration whose budget 
would increase from 12 billion to 14 billion that includes 
almost 577 million in block grant money for drug treatment 
programs an increase of 100 million in such grants 
the third largest dollar increase is for the agency for 
international development moving from 48 million to 224 million 
much of that for the andean countries where most of the worlds 
cocaine is produced the fourth largest increase is for the drug 
enforcement administration from 549 million to 700 million in 
1991 
the designation of the highintensity drug trafficking areas 
applies to 1990 as well as 1991 according to walters the current 
budget allocates 25 million for those areas plus up to 21 
million more from the federal asset forfeiture fund said reggie 
walton associate director of bennetts office and the 1991 budget 
calls for 50 million for those areas 
but carnes said the areas actually will be receiving a total of 
12 billion worth of federal efforts this year and would receive 
a total of 14 billion in 1991 when all other federal programs 
and grants are included 
most of the help will be in the form of money going to federal 
agencies who will target those areas not in checks to the local 
governments 
the strategy listed metropolitan areas and surrounding areas 
that could be included as well as the cities in those surrounding 
areas 
the new york city area could include nassau county in new york 
and union hudson and essex counties in new jersey it said carnes 
said that area would receive 396 million worth of help in 1990 and 
436 million in 1991 
los angeles could include los angeles and orange counties and 
would get 151 million in 1990 and 169 million in 1991 
miami which could include broward dade and monroe counties 
fla could get 196 million in 1990 and 223 million in 1991 
houston which could include harris and galveston counties 
texas could get 168 million in 1990 and 187 million in 1991 
the southwest border includes 35 counties in california 
arizona new mexico and texas would receive 330 million in 1990 
and 368 million in 1991 
the total number of federal antidrug workers targeted to each 
area is new york 250 los angeles 300 miami 300 houston 200 
southwest border 700 carnes said 
