<TEXT>
czechoslovak president vaclav havel made a 
sentimental visit thursday to the warsaw theater where his plays 
were staged until the 1981 martiallaw ban and then revived as 
poland turned to democracy 
the teatr powczechny brought the playwrights work to audiences 
last year even while havel still was banned in czechoslovakia 
havel who was elected president dec 29 after czechoslovakias 
velvet revolution included a trip to the theater during an 
official trip to poland 
standing amid the crates and cages that form the set for one of 
his plays havel discussed characterizations and dialogue with the 
actors 
as havel signed underground copies of his plays one actor said 
he hoped he would not face arrest if he performed the presidents 
works in prague 
probably no havel replied the foreign minister is my 
close friend and he always asks me about everything 
havel was greeted by the theaters director andrzej wajda an 
internationally acclaimed filmmaker who said he felt he was 
welcoming the president home 
this is his house we are performing his plays he is our 
writer and that is why we consider us to be havels home in 
warsaw wajda said 
the director recalled the theater gave 11 performances of 
havels plays in 1981 before the martiallaw declaration that 
crushed solidarity and the cultural outpouring that accompanied the 
independent movement 
the home theater now presenting havels works at the 
powczechny was created by actors who performed banned works 
including his at private homes during the martiallaw period 
wajda said 
</TEXT>
