<TEXT>
president vaclav havel of czechoslovakia 
proposed thursday that his country poland and hungary work in 
unison to return to europe following decades of soviet 
domination 
he also called for an international peace conference that 
would put the definite period mark to world war ii and the cold 
war and the artificial division of germany and europe 
the goal is clear havel said 
we want to belong to a europe that is a friendly community of 
independent states a stable europe a europe that does not need 
protection from superpowers because it is capable of defending 
itself by constructing its own security system he said 
the ongoing helsinki treaty process and parallel disarmament 
talks should be accelerated to prepare the way to the peace 
conference he said 
then both military pacts could be dissolved and the process of 
alleuropean integration could be started including the 
reunification of germany within the present borders of east and 
west germany he said 
the former dissident playwright elected president last month 
after czechoslovakias peaceful anticommunist revolution told the 
polish national assembly that joint action to rejoin western europe 
would avert rivalry among eastern europes emerging democracies 
we should not compete in who is going to overtake whom and who 
will be first to win a seat in some european body but we should do 
just the opposite help each other in the spirit of that solidarity 
with which in worse times you protested against our repression and 
we against yours havel told the joint session of the polish sejm 
and senate 
western europe is much more advanced in integration processes 
and if we were to return to europe individually it would certainly 
take much longer and it would be much more complicated that if we 
act together he said 
this does not only concern economics it concerns everything 
including disarmament talks he said 
politicians in czechoslovakia hungary and poland support the 
withdrawal of soviet troops from their territory but each country 
has been discussing the issue separately with moscow 
havel said a power vacuum has existed in central europe since 
the collapse of the habsburg empire at the end of world war he 
said the countries of the region until recently colonized by 
the soviets should unite in a new formation 
such a grouping would not appear to rich western europe as an 
impoverished and helplesslooking amnestied prisoner but as 
someone who can also contribute something he said 
but havel said he could not predict the institutional shape 
of the proposed cooperation among the three countries 
he proposed that czechoslovakia host representatives of poland 
and hungary at the bratislava castle near the hungarian and 
austrian borders to discuss the form of alliance observers from 
other eastern european countries could also attend and eventually 
might join in the cooperative effort he said 
a polish government spokesman henryk wozniakowski said poland 
looks positively on havels proposition and would certainly 
be willing to take part in such talks 
havels speech was the high point of his oneday trip to poland 
his first since his student days in 1956 he planned to take his 
proposal on european integration to hungary on friday 
he was warmly received in parliament and was serenaded afterward 
by members with a round of sto lat may he live 100 years 
the audience chuckled when havel recalled the first meeting of 
czechoslovak and polish dissidents in the mountains along the two 
countries border in 1978 
he recalled how he jan litynski and adam michnik now both 
solidarity members of the polish parliament and jacek kuron the 
current labor minister laughed about being able to duck 
surveillance for the clandestine meeting 
if someone had told us then that in 12 years we would be 
deputies ministers and presidents then we would have laughed even 
more havel said 
in the visits only discordant note havel did not meet with 
solidarity leader lech walesa who refused an invitation citing 
prior plans to meet shipyard workers in gdansk and saying he did 
not want to have handshaking with no results walesa instead 
sent greetings to havel 
havel was welcomed thursday at warsaws military airport by 
communist president wojciech jaruzelski senior government 
officials a full military honor guard and the diplomatic corps 
he laid a wreath at the grave of the rev jerzy popieluszko the 
prosolidarity priest murdered by security police in 1984 it was 
the first time that an eastern european state leader had visited 
the grave 
about 1000 poles turned out to see havel who wrote in the 
guest book at st stanislaw kostka church where popieluszko is 
buried i have been moved for the first time since i became 
president 
he also visited a theater company that has been performing two 
of his plays for nearly a year when they still were banned in 
czechoslovakia 
</TEXT>
