<TEXT>
the japanese now own the publick house 
inn and run the food concession at historic old sturbridge village 
but the venerable yankee institutions promise tofu and sushi wont 
replace turkey and succotash 
this is an institution its a bastion of yankee cuisine 
said buddy adler innkeeper at the publick house historic inn 
built in 1771 by a revolutionary war hero it is what is to 
change it nobody would even contemplate that 
the inn a cluster of white colonial buildings dotted about the 
town common also runs the food service concession at old 
sturbridge village a living museum that recreates massachusetts 
life in the early 19th century 
crawford lincoln director of the nonprofit group that runs the 
village said thursday that he too doesnt expect any changes now 
that a japanese company owns the villages eateries 
indian pudding not sushi will be the order of the day from 
the food service he said 
the changes took place earlier this week when kyotaru co a 
japanese food service company bought restaurant associates of new 
york city for an undisclosed sum restaurant associates has six 
divisions with 120 fullservice restaurants and generates about 
240 million in annual revenue said company spokesman dennis 
rhodes in new york 
in the deal six top managers retained 15 percent of restaurant 
associates and will continue to operate the business hiroshi 
tanaka chairman of kyotaru will also be chairman of restaurant 
associates 
the acquisition included another venerable landmark the 
84yearold italian restaurant mamma leones in new york city 
rhodes said 
although the food will remain the same adler said he did not 
know whether japanese ownership will have any effect on the 
ambiance of the publick house which includes a 110room motor 
lodge and another restaurant and is listed on the national register 
of historic places 
the change will mean an infusion of capital and that could fuel 
expansion he said 
that was welcome news to sturbridge town administrator kevin 
walsh 
from the standpoint of the town of sturbridge infusion of 
capital probably means additional expansion and additional tax 
dollars if thats accurate thats certainly a positive note 
walsh said 
sturbridge a small town of about 7700 in central 
massachusetts draws thousands of tourists each year the 
population doubles to about 15000 during summer months 
about 350000 people come to see old sturbridge village to 
witness life in a recreated new england farm village the main 
restaurant is bullard tavern whose menu features such yankee 
staples as chicken pot pie and cranberry sauce 
old sturbridge village is a nonprofit living history that 
sets forth life in rural new england in the early 19th century and 
as such we will continue to hold fast to all aspects of the new 
england experience lincoln said 
he said the change of ownership could mean more visitors from 
the far east 
when visitors do arrive they will be pleased to find we have 
our map guide already printed in japanese said lincoln 
