<TEXT>
a former bath iron works employee fired 
after complaining to the navy that some steel used in war ships 
allegedly was not inspected cannot have a jury trial maines 
highest court ruled thursday 
leon e bard jr contends in his wrongful firing lawsuit that he 
lost his job for whistle blowing but biw said he was dismissed for 
inadequate job performance 
it will go to trial before a judge biw attorney constance 
p oneil said after the high court ruled that bard had no grounds 
for appealing a superior court ruling that took his case off a list 
of lawsuits to be heard by jurors 
the justices of the maine supreme judicial court ruled 
unanimously that they are able to consider appeals only when cases 
have proceeded farther than bards case had gone 
ms oneil expected a trial date will be set soon in superior 
court in augusta 
bard a quality assurance inspector was fired by biw in 
september 1986 after several years in which he had complained 
about allegedly uninspected steel used in ticonderoga class 
cruisers to the supervisor of shipbuilding an onsite navy office 
that keeps an eye on biws construction of warships in bath 
the navy investigated bards charges first after he made an 
initial complaint and a second time when he complained again after 
being fired and found no problems with the biw steel ms oneil 
said 
bards firing had nothing to do with his whistleblowing biw 
said 
he was fired for being a lessthanadequate employee ms 
oneil said there were others who were making the same kinds of 
suggestions who are still there if they biw managers were 
worried about them they would have gotten rid of all of them 
there was no immediate comment from bard no phone number is 
listed for him in the bath area his attorney elliott l epstein 
of lewiston was not immediately available for comment thursday 
according to a secretary 
ms oneil said she was not certain what bard was seeking in his 
lawsuit but she believed he wanted back pay and possibly 
reinstatement 
bard initially filed a fourcount lawsuit against biw and the 
superior court dismissed three counts leaving one that alleged 
bards firing violated the maine whistleblowers protection act 
the lower court said that case would have to be tried by a judge 
and not a jury leading to bards appeal to the high court 
