dogies and rode into town thursday to duel lyrics with bards from 
down under about life on the open range at the sixth annual cowboy 
poetry gathering 
more than 70 cowboy poets from 16 western states and six 
australians are scheduled to trade lore about riding roping and 
the wild but dangerous thrill of taming bucking bulls and broncs 
elko a 4hour drive to reno and a little more to salt lake 
city is expected to more than double its 3500 population through 
saturday in the gathering that has gained national attention 
i think people will be surprised to find they australians 
basically have a parallel tradition to our cowboy poetry 
tradition said hal cannon cofounder of the event 
they have a similar stockmen tradition and their history of 
settling the outback is similar to our settling the west 
this years gathering is dedicated to curley fletcher one of 
the original cowboy poets who learned their craft sitting around a 
nighttime campfire 
fletcher who died in 1954 published poems about the west 
including a 1931 rhyme called strawberry roan in which a wild 
bronc gives the poems cowboy a hard time in the saddle and finally 
throws him to the ground 
in the last stanza the cowboy gives the strawberry roan his due 
then i knows that the hosses i aint able tuh ride 
is some of them living they havent all died 
but i bets all muh money they aint no man alive 
kin stay with that bronk when he makes that high dive 
