the state department said thursday that 
romanias new leaders had gone too far in banning protests in 
bucharest and urged them to reconfirm their commitment to 
democracy 
the criticism contrasted with earlier bush administration 
support for the national salvation front the provisonal romanian 
leadership that took over in december after hardliner nicolae 
ceausescu was executed 
there have been reports that secretary of state james a baker 
iii might visit romania next month in conjunction with his trip to 
the soviet union and czechoslovakia but state department officials 
say no decision has been made about such a step baker arrives in 
moscow feb 6 for talks over the next two days with kremlin leaders 
we are deeply concerned about news reports that the decision 
of the national salvation front has imposed restrictions on 
demonstrations in bucharest said state department spokeswoman 
margaret tutwiler 
the romanian government issued its decree jan 3 in response to 
demonstrations and reissued it after a protest wednesday by 1000 
people demanding that the front refrain from taking part in 
elections set for may the decree outlaws demonstrations in 
bucharest and allows them only in some parks unless the protests 
are approved by police 48 hours in advance 
the right of citizens to express their opinions peacefully 
including the ability to march and demonstrate is a fundamental 
human right tutwiler said 
while we recognize that civil authorities may enact reasonable 
regulations to ensure public safety these restrictions appear to 
go well beyond this need 
some members of the front have been critical of the united 
states for not providing more economic help to their country and 
have asked for the restoration of trade concessions that ceausescu 
gave up 
the state department has indicated that any decision by congress 
and the administration on the trade concessions would depend on 
steps by the romanian government toward free elections 
the nsfs latest action is all the more disturbing in view of 
the fronts solemn pledge to the romanian people to build a 
pluralistic democracy and respect human rights as well as to carry 
out free fair and open national elections tutwiler said 
we call upon the nsf to reassure the romanian people and the 
international community that it remains committed to moving forward 
toward democracy she added 
