<TEXT>
pope john paul ii began a 
tour of the impoverished sahel region south of the sahara by asking 
rich countries thursday not to abandon poor nations in favor of 
eastern europe 
the holy see and the pope feel allied with africa and 
other countries of the third world he told reporters on the 
flight from rome to this former portuguese colony off west africa 
we must present to the rich all the needs of the poor we must 
insist on solutions how can you not cry out in certain 
situations 
on the first stop of an eightday trip john paul also urged 
peaceful resolution through dialogue of crises in the soviet union 
including the violence in azerbaijan 
these are especially painful events we seek to participate in 
the events above all with prayer he said in response to the 
first soviet journalist to join one of the popes foreign tours a 
reporter for the labor newspaper trud 
asked what message he would send president mikhail s gorbachev 
the pontiff said i would wish him above all the gift of good 
advice 
john paul referred to his historic meeting with gorbachev on 
dec 1 at the vatican and said the soviet leader realized the 
importance of spirituality in his communist country 
perhaps i can say without betraying any personal secret 
gorbachev was very pleased with the popes prayers he said 
prayer is certainly a sign of spiritual order spiritual values 
and that we have a great need for these values 
to a question about how much violence could be justified in the 
us invasion of panama and the soviet military intervention in 
azerbaijan he replied that violence is always something morally 
negative morally bad 
he did not refer directly to either of the cases but said 
selfdefense could be justifiable in some situations 
we cannot deny the right of the socalled just war to this 
selfdefense either of an individual community or a people when it 
has suffered violence on the part of others the pope said 
his sixth voyage to africa the 45th foreign trip of his 
11yearold pontificate comes at a time when african leaders worry 
that their persistent need for aid will be pushed aside in the rush 
to support emerging democratic movements in eastern europe 
noting the current focus on that region which includes his 
native poland the pontiff said developed countries cannot 
abandon their common responsibility for the south for the problems 
of the third world 
for this i can thank providence that my journey is taking me 
precisely to africa this is an act of providence 
john paul emphasized that the duty to help poor nations falls on 
all countries of the north in which he included the soviet 
union and its allies 
cape verde and the other nations on his itinerary 
guineabissau mali burkina faso and chad are in the sahel a 
region afflicted by drought hunger disease and encroaching 
deserts 
i am traveling in african countries which are the poorest 
the pope said this trip is especially dear to me because we are 
going to meet the poor in the economic and material sense in a 
moral sense poverty means wealth 
he touched on the same theme in his remarks at praia airport to 
president aristides pereira 
the pontiffs white robes flapped in the strong wind as he 
declared in portuguese 
originally destined for all men the goods of this world will 
never reach this universal destination without the indispensable 
collaboration of the international community in the framework of a 
vast solidarity which includes everyone and responds primarily to 
the needs of the disadvantaged 
at the same time the recipients of aid should not become 
servile but maintain the dignity of the interdependence of 
peoples 
cape verde is an archipelago of 10 islands that gained 
independence in 1975 ninety percent of the 360000 people are 
roman catholic the highest proportion in africa 
john pauls next stop is guineabissau on saturday 
