<TEXT>
americans wages salaries and other benefits 
rose 5 percent last year the government said thursday in a report 
that economists took as a sign that high labor costs may worsen the 
nations inflation problems 
the labor department said its employment cost index considered 
one of the best gauges of inflationary wage pressures showed an 
increase equal to the 5 percent rise in 1988 in employment costs 
rising health care costs in part pushed the index forward both 
years the agency said 
the increases in compensation showed that labor costs are 
failing to moderate despite a slower economy some analysts said 
thats because the slowdown has not pushed the unemployment rate 
much above its 15year low of 5 percent last march the jobless 
rate was 53 percent last month 
the slowdown has been too mild to rein in compensation 
costs said robert dederick chief economist at northern trust 
co of chicago while this is good in the shortterm for the 
worker it raises the question that inflation is going to 
increase 
allen sinai chief economist at the boston co called the 
report disappointing because its very hard for me to believe 
that overall inflation will come down much 
benefit costs jumped 61 percent in 1989 compared to a 68 
percent gain in 1988 but the 1988 increase was attributed in part 
to a 5 percent increase in the employers social security tax rate 
escalating health insurance costs last year kept the cost of 
benefits high even without a big change in the social security tax 
the labor department said 
before 1988 benefit costs had grown consistently for the past 
three years at about 35 percent 
its going to be a steady fight to bring that down 
economist cynthia latta of drimcgraw hill said of the 61 percent 
hike in benefit costs theyre trying to pass this on to workers 
and thats going to take a while 
while overall employment costs rose wage and salary increases 
lagged behind inflation for the third straight year they grew by 
42 percent in 1989 under the years 46 percent inflation rate 
in 1988 wages and salaries were up 41 percent while inflation was 
44 percent 
according to the labor department employment costs for state 
and local government workers rose 62 percent up from 56 percent 
in 1988 
it cost private industry employers 48 percent more last year to 
pay wages salaries and benefits than it did in 1988 the 
department said compared with a 49 percent gain in 1988 over 
1987 federal government costs are not included in the report 
sales workers whose pay is heavily influenced by commissions 
experienced a 7 percent wage jump in 1989 compared with a 66 
percent gain in 1988 and just a 1 percent gain in 1987 
workers in the rapidly expanding service sector of the economy 
where the tight labor market is felt experienced a 45 percent 
wage gain while those working in goodsproducing industries saw 
their pay increase on average by 39 percent 
for the sixth straight year nonunion workers in private 
industry received greater wage and salary increases than did their 
unionized counterparts with the increases averaging 41 percent 
and 31 percent respectively 
state and local government workers received on average a 53 
percent pay gain in 1989 up from the 48 percent increase of 1988 
with the increase in that sector highest among hospital workers 
who averaged 61 percent pay raises 
