president bushs plan to spend about 106 
billion on the war against drugs in 1991 sticks to a 
heavyonlawenforcement theme with almost fourfifths of the 
money devoted to enforcement at home and abroad 
at the same time the proposed drug war budget up almost 12 
percent from this years spending of 95 billion would hike 
treatment funds by 12 percent to 15 billion and education 
community and workplace useprevention funds by 11 percent to 12 
billion 
the breakdown comes to 42 percent for domestic law enforcement 
29 percent for border drug interdiction and international 
operations and 29 percent for demand reduction said john walters 
chief of staff to drug policy director william j bennett 
to those who say our program looks topheavy on the 
interdiction side remember that many of the efforts to limit 
supply are exclusively federal and inherently more expensive than 
demand reduction bush said in a speech to newspaper publishers 
as he unveiled the updated version of the strategy announced in 
september 
were willing to spend more to limit the drug supply simply 
put were willing to do whatever it takes 
if congress goes along with bush local and state officials will 
get their hands on 26 billion or about onefourth of the total 
through grants for law enforcement treatment and prevention 
efforts a 108 percent increase over the last two years 
the five regions designated as highintensity drugtrafficking 
areas new york los angeles miami houston and the southwest 
border of california arizona new mexico and texas will benefit 
from total federal efforts of about 12 billion this year and if 
congress approves 14 billion in 1991 
the agency that would get the largest chunk of the 106 billion 
is the alcohol drug abuse and mental health administration part 
of the department of health and human services which would be 
given 14 billion of that 577 million would be for block grants 
for drugtreatment programs an increase of 100 million 
the agency that would receive the second largest amount is the 
pentagon with 12 million of which 638 million would go for 
detection and monitoring of drug traffickers crossing the us 
borders and 227 million would be for operational costs such as 
flying and sailing time walters said 
the state departments agency for international development 
would get 224 million up from 48 million much of the money 
would go to aid the andean countries where most of the worlds 
cocaine is produced 
the drug enforcement administration would get 700 million up 
from 549 million to raise the number of dea personnel from 5224 
to 5601 elsewhere in law enforcement the budget envisions money 
for about 410 additional federal prosecutors an additional 100 fbi 
workers and 75 new federal judges 
overall criminal justice spending would increase 2 percent to 
43 billion international initiatives would shoot up 65 percent 
to 690 million interdiction efforts would increase 17 percent to 
24 billion research would rise 20 percent to 383 million and 
intelligence efforts would zoom up 142 percent to 172 million 
in other areas the drug strategy 
calls for almost doubling funds for eradication of domestic 
marijuana production to 35 million in 1991 this was done in 
part walters said to show foreign governments urged by the united 
states to stamp out their drug production that the us government 
is serious about wiping out domestically produced supplies as well 
envisions spending 400 million in prevention and treatment for 
pregnant women who use drugs and for their children part of an 
effort to combat the problem of cocaine babies and those born 
addicted to other drugs 
continues the andean strategy launched last september by 
spending 22 billion over five years in drug law enforcement and 
economic development funds for colombia peru and bolivia the 
proposed budget would increase from 217 million in 1990 to 423 
million in 1991 including 50 million in additional aid for 
colombia walters said 
the five areas of the country designated as highintensity 
drugtrafficking areas appear on the surface to be slated to 
receive only 25 million this year and 50 million next year 
but they actually will receive help worth a total of about 12 
billion this year and presuming congress agrees 14 billion next 
year most of the aid would be in the form of additional federal 
agents assigned to those areas to enhance law enforcement and 
interdiction efforts but some of that money will come in the form 
of block grants similar to those being given out nationwide 
