<TEXT>
president gen ibrahim babangida signed a 
decree thursday reducing the military governments power to detain 
people without charge from six months to six weeks 
the decree imposed in 1984 permitted senior government 
officials to order the detention without charge of people deemed to 
be security threats the detention orders allowed detention of up 
to a halfyear and could be renewed 
the new decree limits detentions to six weeks at which time 
they can be renewed but must be reviewed by a panel made up of 
government officials religious leaders a retired judge a 
representative of the nigerian bar association and others 
the decree also authorizes only the general chief of staff of 
the military to order detentions previously the minister of 
international affairs and inspector general of police also had the 
power to authorize detentions 
in announcing the amendments justice minister bola ajibola said 
the government was bowing to demands for a relaxation of the decree 
from human rights groups and the bar association 
</TEXT>
