president bush vowing to do whatever it 
takes proposed a 11 billion increase thursday for the war 
against drugs targeting more money for a pentagon attack on 
cocaine traffickers and urging the death penalty for drug kingpins 
overall bushs package would total 106 billion and boost the 
cost of the nations drugfighting strategy in fiscal 1991 by 116 
percent over current spending of 95 billion 
a rival plan from the chairman of the senate judiciary 
committee sen joseph biden ddel would cost 146 billion 
give the presidents drug policy coordinator cabinet status and 
outlaw semiautomatic weapons 
bush said he expects the senate will try to approve a higher 
budget than he is asking but said we do sense a desire on the 
part of the congress to cooperate 
in terms of the objectives of this strategy were in pretty 
close accord with both democrats and republicans on the hill so i 
think we can get early action bush said early congressional 
reaction split predictably along party lines 
calling drugs this nations no 1 concern bush announced 
his proposal in a white house speech to newspaper editors 
the plan is the second phase of the drug war strategy unveiled 
in september and targets five areas for intensified federal 
drugfighting efforts 
while claiming progress in the drug war bush said given the 
headlines weve seen recently its clear were only getting 
started 
in response to a question bush said he felt great sadness 
great tragedy over the arrest of district of columbia mayor 
marion barry on misdemeanor cocaine charges 
my thought went to the kids kids in the schools its a 
matter of sadness and barbara bushs wife shares my view on 
this 
the president also vowed to hold the line against proposals 
to legalize drugs 
were willing to spend more to limit the drug supply bush 
said calling his package a blueprint for success 
simply put were willing to do whatever it takes he said 
his plan designates five regions new york los angeles miami 
houston and the southwest border of california arizona new mexico 
and texas as highintensity drugtrafficking areas 
federal antidrug efforts in those areas will benefit from 
millions of dollars in additional federal help this year and next 
the current budget allocates 25 million for the worstafflicted 
areas plus up to 21 million more from the federal asset 
forfeiture fund said reggie walton associate director of 
bennetts office the 1991 budget calls for 50 million for those 
areas 
bush said onethird of his drugcontrol budget would go toward 
education prevention and treatment programs another third to 
domestic enforcement and the final third for border interdiction 
and international operations 
bennetts office however said that 29 percent of the money 
would go for education and other demandreduction efforts 42 
percent for domestic enforcement and 29 percent for border 
interdiction and international efforts 
the largest spending increase would go to the pentagon to expand 
its drugfighting role it would receive 12 billion up from 
about 878 million in the current fiscal year which ends sept 30 
about 638 million of the pentagon funds would be earmarked for 
detection and monitoring of traffickers trying to enter the country 
with illicit drugs 
moreover the plan envisions ship and aircraftdetection 
activities in the caribbean sea in concert with foreign 
governments 
our approach remains consistent to reduce use through an 
integrated mix of supply and demandside approaches and that 
means doing everything that works bush said 
the secondlargest increase would be for the department of 
health and human services alcohol drug abuse and mental health 
administration which would have its budget increased from 12 
billion to 14 billion 
that includes almost 577 million in block grant money for 
drugtreatment programs an increase of 100 million 
bush said he was proposing an increase in fbi and drug 
enforcement agents as well as 75 new federal judges 
we are proposing the death penalty for drug kingpins and those 
responsible for drugrelated killings and even in some cases 
attempted killings bush said 
we want there to be absolutely no doubt about the certainty of 
punishment he said currently the maximum penalty for leaders 
of continuing criminal enterprises is life imprisonment 
we want the multinational criminal organizations that produce 
and distribute drugs to be more than disrupted we intend to see 
them dismantled and destroyed because we dont make deals with 
dealers bush said 
he also praised efforts by the leaders of mexico and colombia in 
fighting drug traffickers and said said he would reinforce our 
support for the courageous leaders of the region at the feb 15 
drug summit in colombia 
congressional reaction to the president split largely along 
party lines with democrats saying more money is needed to get to 
