liberian soldiers accused of 
massacring civilians are leaving few survivors in their relentless 
search for rebels near the ivory coast border diplomats and 
medical workers said thursday 
they tell really horrendous stories of soldiers spraying 
entire villages with 50caliber machine guns a western diplomat 
said bullets from such heavy weapons tear huge holes in bodies 
the diplomat and ivorian sources estimated at least 500 
civilians had been killed in liberias eastern nimba region since 
soldiers were sent to stop rebel attacks that began dec 24 
refugees say there are not many wounded people because the 
soldiers slaughtered so many the diplomat said he visited 
refugees tuesday with ivorian officials aid workers and other 
diplomats from nations donating food medicine and money 
officials fear an outbreak of disease because of a stream of 
refugees estimated thursday to number more than 60000 about 
12000 to 15000 other liberians have sought refuge in guinea the 
diplomat said 
at the ivorian border village of danane refugees tell of 
dashing to safety in the forest when they hear the daily 
machinegun fire across the frontier 
they are traumatized by the combat and watching some of their 
relatives being killed said claude regnier a french adviser to 
the ivory coast government who heads a committee coordinating aid 
to the refugees 
when the gunfire starts they rush to the forest and come out 
only when it stops he said in an interview 
a western diplomat said the killing began in liberia after 
rebels from the gio tribe increased attacks in an attempt to oust 
president samuel doe who seized power in 1980 from the descendants 
of freed american slaves who founded the west african nation in 
1847 the gio long have felt oppressed by does krahn tribe 
it started with gio rebels attacking military outposts in 
their own ethnic heartland in nimba county the diplomat said 
also speaking on condition of anonymity the army came in and 
just went nuts because everyone looks like a rebel to them there 
has been some very heavyhanded slaughter 
the rebels retaliated about 10 days ago by moving south into 
traditional krahn territory and slaughtering civilians there he 
said that caused a second wave of victims to flee east into ivory 
coast and north into guinea he said 
killings of innocent people continue despite a warning from doe 
on monday that soldiers who harmed civilians would be executed the 
diplomat said 
