sister r mildred barker the 
spiritual leader of maines tiny shaker community died thursday 
after an extended illness she was 92 
her death leaves just eight shakers in the last active maine 
community of the protestant faith said leonard brooks director of 
the shaker museum in gloucester where the group has its 1900acre 
farm 
a religous sect that flourished in the 19th century shakerism 
practices celibacy and a communal life revolving around worship and 
farming 
sister mildred was put in charge in 1931 of the shakers jelly 
and jam industry as well as a candymaking business she made 
sales trips as far away as boston and sold eggs in portland maine 
the shakers said in a statement 
in 1950 she was chosen trustee of the community overseeing 
business and financial matters the community raises sheep and 
grows apples and herbs 
sister mildred was born in providence ri on feb 3 1897 
and at age 7 after her father died her mother placed her among the 
shakers brooks said 
brooks said former president ronald reagan recognized sister 
mildred in 1983 for her expertise in singing old shaker songs many 
of which were recorded on four albums 
sister mildreds single greatest delight was singing the 
beautiful old shaker hymns that had been taught to her in her 
youth the statement said she personally knew thousands of 
songs and sought to preserve them 
</TEXT>
