<TEXT>
authorities raised the death toll from 
flooding this week to at least 24 with another 32 people missing 
and thousands homeless the official news agency tap reported 
thursday 
the torrential rains that struck the north african country on 
monday slackened thursday as the united nations and foreign 
countries responded to a government appeal for food tents water 
pumps and other emergency aid 
floodwaters receded in central and southern tunisia normally 
arid regions that were hit hardest by the storm and overland links 
were reestablished with the communities of sidi bouzid gafsa 
gabes tozeur and kasserine tap reported 
about 14000 homes were destroyed in the flooding tap said and 
thousands of homeless people sought shelter in schools mosques and 
public buildings the health ministry issued a statement saying 
there appeared no risk of an epidemic 
the news agency earlier reported a riot wednesday by islamic 
fundamentalists in the central city of sidi bouzid where 13 people 
died tap said 
about 800 sympathizers of the outlawed fundamentalist movement 
an nahda hurled rocks at government buildings and burned a parked 
car as they paraded around the body of a person they said had died 
in the floods tap reported 
police arrested 26 people in the demonstration 
tap said the protesters expressed their hostility toward the 
tunisian educational system without any relationship to the 
situation brought on by the flooding 
