<TEXT>
the food and drug administrations warning 
against an american heart association foodlabeling plan was 
criticized thursday by a consumer group and at least one food 
company wanting to display the plans seal of approval on its 
products 
the association said it will begin heartguide on monday 
despite the fdas warning that participating companies could face 
enforcement action if their products are found to be mislabeled 
and will stick to its plan to extend the labels to more foods 
the heartguide program puts an association heart healthy 
seal on approved products 
two of the nine companies with heartguideapproved products said 
they will remain in the program though their packaging with the 
heartguide seal wont go on sale until midfebrary or march the 
other companies either had not yet decided how to react to the 
warning or did not return telephone calls 
bruce silverglade legal director of the center for science in 
the public interest an advocacy group that frequently seeks 
tougher food and drug regulations said that while he shares some 
of the fdas concerns about heartguide the agencys action is 
premature and unfortunate 
the federal government has defaulted on its obligation to 
control misleading health claims by food manufacturers and the 
heart associations plan does represent an attempt to provide some 
reliable health information to consumers he said 
he said the fda has been trying for several years to adopt a 
regulation restricting health claims that food manufacturers can 
put on their labels 
the agency has also been criticized for moving too slowly to 
revise requirements for food labeling in general the fda held 
hearings last fall on food labeling and plans to draft a proposal 
by summer a spokesman said 
in a letter to the association wednesday the fda expressed 
concern that the heartguide program will increase consumer 
confusion and could lead to endorsement of some margarine and oil 
products that do not represent the kinds of foods that ought to 
be promoted to achieve healthy hearts 
silverglade said he shares that concern and added that the 
association may be giving out the seal a little to generously and 
that their standards were not strict enough 
for the first phase of the program more than 100 brands of 
margarine oil crackers and vegetables have been tested and 
approved they include mazola corn oil promise margarine pam 
cooking sprays melba toast and hanover frozen vegetables 
companies pay a fee up to 640000 depending on sales to 
participate in the program 
in the second phase which initially was put on hold after the 
fda letter but put back on track thursday the seal will be offered 
to other products including cereals cheese cookies pasta salad 
dressings and other foods 
the fda has no authority to stop the program but it could take 
companies to court if it finds their labels misrepresent their 
products 
one of the companies in the program said it intends to advertise 
its seal of approval despite the fda warning 
i dont think im afraid of it because i think there will be a 
resolution to the problem said bob maier chairman of california 
amp washington co a san franciscobased company that markets frozen 
vegetables i think both groups are trying to do best for the 
consumer 
he noted that other thirdparty endorsements including the good 
housekeeping seal of approval and the american dental association 
are being used now to guide consumers in other markets 
