the budget president bush will propose monday 
will include about 50 million to improve government statistics 
affecting most americans ranging from costofliving wage 
increases to prices of stocks in which pension funds invest 
heavily the presidents chief economic adviser said thursday 
contending that the us statistical system is among the finest 
in the world chairman michael j boskin of the council of economic 
advisers admitted it still has serious problems especially in the 
rapidly changing areas where accuracy is most needed 
the economic statistics are important because of their large 
impact on the economy boskin said at a news briefing on bushs 
initiative to improve economic statistics 
private orders and contracts costofliving adjustments the 
federal budget and monetary policy are all based on the economic 
information produced by the federal statistical system he added 
boskin said various government agencies are expected to report 
in about three months on how they plan to implement 25 
recommendations already made by the presidential economic policy 
councils working group to improve the system 
boskin who heads the group said the most serious problem 
facing the governments statisticsgathering operation is 
estimating quality change in many important sectors 
when we as a nation produced mostly things like steel and 
wheat output was easy to count tons of steel and bushels of 
wheat he said 
today a larger share of output is in sectors where better 
performance means quality and improved convenience he continued 
consider the impact of 24hour automatic teller machines and the 
changes in desktop and laptop computers 
as an example of the need to examine measurement problems 
boskin cited price indexes that should adjust for quality change 
when the commerce department recently introduced a new 
computer price index that only partially adjusted for quality 
change it raised real gnp gross antional product growth from 38 
to 41 percent a difference reaching 70 billion by 1988 and 
lowered the rate in inflation as measured by the gnp price 
deflator from 36 to 33 percent between 1982 and 1988 he said 
boskin also said the governments statistical system has not 
kept up with changes in the economy including airline 
deregulation which he said produced lower fares and widespread 
discounting causing passenger miles to increase by over 60 percent 
in the 1980s 
yet the price index is still heavily based on fullfare 
tickets which now account for only 10 percent of tickets he 
noted 
</TEXT>
