<TEXT>
the revised national drug control strategy 
unveiled thursday by president bush carries a price tag of 106 
billion for 1991 up 11 billion from the current 95 billion in 
spending here at a glance are the main features of the proposal 
most of which needs congressional approval 
of the total spending 42 percent would be for domestic law 
enforcement 29 percent for drug interdiction at the borders and 
international operations and 29 percent for demand reduction 
including prevention and treatment 
treatment funds would increase by 12 percent to 15 billion 
antidrug education and community and workplace programs to prevent 
drug abuse would get 12 billion an 11 percent increase research 
would increase by 20 percent to 383 million 
criminal justice funds would increase by 2 percent to 43 
billion interdiction efforts would increase by 17 percent to 24 
billion international initiatives would rise by 65 percent to 690 
million and intelligence budgets would go up by 142 percent to 
172 million 
the strategy calls for expanding the circumstances under which 
drug kingpins could face the death penalty including cases in 
which they or their organizations have not killed anyone when they 
try to kill in order to obstruct justice or when their offenses 
result in death such as a drug users overdose 
about 26 billion of the total budget would be distributed to 
state and local governments in the form of block grants for law 
enforcement drug treatment and antidrug education programs 
five areas are designated as highintensity drugtrafficking 
areas new york los angeles miami houston and the southwest 
border of california arizona new mexico and texas although the 
budget specifically mentions spending 25 million extra for those 
areas this year and 50 million next year officials said total 
federal antidrug spending in the five regions would be 12 
billion this year and 14 billion next year 
the andean strategy of buttressing the drugfighting efforts of 
the main cocaineproducing countries of colombia peru and bolivia 
with 22 billion in drug law enforcement and economic development 
aid over five years continues increasing from 217 million in 1990 
to 423 million in 1991 including 50 million in additional aid 
for colombia 
pregnant women who use drugs and their drugaddicted babies 
would be targeted with 400 million in prevention and treatment 
funds 
new attention is focused on eradicating domestic marijuana 
fields with a virtual doubling of federal funds to 35 million 
the pentagon takes a much more significant role in the drug war 
with a budget of 12 billion up from 878 million this year with 
638 million to be used for detection and monitoring of drug 
traffickers crossing the us borders 
</TEXT>
