the american federation of teachers said 
thursday it will help educators in eastern european countries and 
others emerging from dictatorship teach the principles and 
practices of democracy and the operation of teachers unions 
the project named education for democracyinternational 
will begin immediately in poland where a delegation will hold a 
seminar sunday for teachers solidarity to give advice on collective 
bargaining and negotiating 
albert shanker president of the union said that the polish 
efforts will be a pilot program that can be repeated in other 
countries requests already have arrived from union leaders and 
educators in hungary chile south africa and czechoslovakia he 
said 
people in romania bulgaria czechoslovakia east germany 
hungary poland and elsewhere are not only trying to recover from 
years of political and economic repression but they also are trying 
to build democratic states shanker said we owe it to them to 
do whatever we can to help 
diane ravitch a professor at teachers college of columbia 
university in new york city said the two oneweek sessions will 
try to give more than 50 leading teachers and union leaders the 
opportunity to decide for themselves what democratic structures 
will best serve their members 
we dont come pushing ourselves or anything that we do 
explained ms ravitch we will deal with questions like how to 
