<TEXT>
raising unemployment taxes now would prevent 
painful increases during a possible recession sponsors said 
thursday as they introduced legislation to raise an extra 26 
billion a year from those taxes by 1993 
the plan by three house democrats comes at a time when many 
members of congress are discussing a cut in the social security 
payroll tax which would provide millions of workers with a tax cut 
one of the sponsors rep tom downey of new york chairman of 
the ways and means subcommittee on human resources said the two 
issues should not be linked because social security funds are 
flushed at the current time and unemployment accounts are not 
he said workers have historically supported unemployment programs 
because they stand to benefit from them 
the aflcio supports the plan said a spokeswoman 
downey noting president bushs nonewtaxes campaign pledge 
defended the measure as merely an expansion of an old tax that has 
not kept pace with increases in the amount of benefits paid to 
unemployed americans 
the white house has not reviewed the legislation or taken a 
stand said spokesman stephen hart 
the measure would make other changes in unemployment 
compensation law such as allowing exmilitary personnel to receive 
benefits for 26 weeks just like civilians out of work instead of 
the 13 weeks now permitted 
downey said there is now an 11 billion shortfall in federal 
unemployment compensation accounts including the fund used for 
making loans to states so they can make payments 
without some change nearly half the states would run out of 
funds to pay benefits if another recession hits he predicted 
we can pay additional unemployment taxes now during good 
economic times or we can pay more unemployment taxes later when we 
have another recession downey said 
under current law the federal government taxes employers 08 
percent on the first 7000 paid to each employee businesses also 
pay state unemployment taxes on top of that 
though businesses write checks to the government many 
economists believe workers shoulder the actual burden through 
smaller wage increases 
downeys measure would increase the federal wage ceiling to 
10000 by 1000 a year for the next three years 
the current 08 percent tax rate includes a 02 percent surtax 
that is set to expire at the end of 1990 downeys measure would 
allow the surtax to expire 
states must set their taxable wage base at least as high as the 
federal ceiling an increase in the federal ceiling to 10000 
would cause 3000 increases in 17 states and smaller increases in 
another 18 states 
the other sponsors are reps sander levin of michigan and don 
pease of ohio 
