<TEXT>
president bush announced thursday that he will 
nominate former new york state legislator john r dunne to the top 
civil rights job in the justice department a post that has been 
vacant for more than a year 
bushs first choice for the job william lucas failed to win 
senate confirmation last year 
the job has been vacant since december 1988 when william 
bradford reynolds stepped down as assistant attorney general for 
civil rights reynolds provoked controversy by opposing 
affirmativeaction programs that involved racial preferences 
dunne who will turn 60 on sunday has a sparse background on 
civil rights a former chairman of the new york state senate 
judiciary committee he is a graduate of georgetown university and 
yale law school 
colleen oconnor a spokeswoman for the american civil liberties 
union said the new york chapter had for years studied dunnes 
record on civil rights and found it lacking 
i think its fair to say these questions are going to come 
up when dunne is examined by the senate judiciary committee she 
said because he has not built a solid record that i think will 
please the civil rights community 
benjamin hooks executive director of the national association 
for the advancement of colored people said he did not know enough 
about dunne to have formed an opinion 
we wait to see what this mans record is and we will be 
looking at it hooks said 
after initial reports in november that dunne was in line for the 
civil rights post he resigned from the allmale garden city golf 
club which he had belonged to for 32 years his hometown is garden 
city ny 
during most of his 24 years as a state legislator a parttime 
post dunne lived in albany at the fort orange club which until 
1988 barred women 
the white house announced the dunne nomination shortly after 
bush finished a news conference at which he was asked whether he 
agrees with naacp leaders that there is a rising tide of racism 
in the country 
bush said he does not view it as a rising tide but said 
there are some very ugly incidents bush said he shares the 
concerns of the civil rights leaders about the recent wave of 
racial bombings and threats in the south 
the lucas nomination was scuttled by intensive lobbying by civil 
rights groups troubled by lucass lack of legal experience and his 
views that supreme court rulings had not eroded civil rights 
protections under the law the senate judiciary committee rejected 
his nomination aug 1 
lucas a onetime michigan sheriff and wayne county executive is 
now a public liaison official at the justice department a post 
that did not require confirmation 
dunne in an interview with the associated press on wednesday 
said he had reviewed videotapes of the judiciary committees 
grilling of lucas to prepare for his own hearings 
i looked at that video again over the weekend and it was a 
very tough spot they put him in said dunne 
its an altogether different ballgame in washington gosh 
they play for keeps said dunne 
he acknowledged i havent had as much experience as im sure 
many civil rights activists perhaps would like to see 
but dunne said he has been sufficiently involved in civil rights 
to have an understanding and a sensitivity and caring about the 
issue 
dunne has the backing of democratic rep charles rangel an old 
friend and the most powerful black member of new yorks 
congressional delegation dunne is white 
if the president has to pick a republican he couldnt pick a 
more decent person than john dunne rangel said in a recent 
interview 
new york gov mario cuomo in a jan 2 letter to bush called 
dunne an honorable and conscientious public servant an able 
lawyer dedicated to the rule of law a committed family man and a 
very decent person cuomo is also a democrat 
dunne resigned his legislative seat last september after losing 
a contest for majority leader in the republicancontrolled state 
senate he is a partner in a uniondale ny law firm 
attorney general dick thornburgh a longtime friend of dunnes 
noted that dunne was called to attica state prison in 1971 by 
rioting prisoners to help negotiate the end of a stalemate with 
state authorities 
dunne has devoted most of his professional life as a public 
servant dedicated to matters relating to the administration of 
justice including the rights of institutionalized persons and 
increased access by the public to legal services thornburgh said 
</TEXT>
