<TEXT>
a minority party in east germanys 
communistled government resigned its three cabinet posts late 
thursday and called on other coalition partners to do likewise 
the withdrawal by the christian democratic union cdu 
effective feb 9 heightened the crisis of confidence faced by the 
communist government of premier hans modrow 
the official adn news agency also said modrow has been invited 
to visit moscow on tuesday for talks with soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev it said the trip would be a working visit but 
gave no details 
the government was forced earlier thursday to agree to major 
concessions to encourage free enterprise because of growing 
pressure for market reforms and reunification with west germany 
cdu leader lothar de maiziere said the three cdu ministers would 
serve in the 27member cabinet until feb 9 effectively setting a 
deadline for modrow to build a new cabinet that includes 
prodemocracy opposition groups 
adn quoted de maiziere as saying his party took the step to 
make way for negotiations with new parties and groups toward 
formation of a new government and assumes other parties in the 
government will take the same steps 
communists now hold 16 ministerial posts liberal democrats 
four christian democrats three and the national democrats and 
farmers party two each 
de maiziere is a deputy premier the two other cdu cabinet 
members are construction minister gerhard baumgaertel and post 
minister klaus wolf 
the cdu threatened on jan 17 to pull out of the government to 
protest the communists tight grip on power 
the noncommunist cabinet members are all from officially 
recognized parties once aligned with the communists all have tried 
to distance themselves from a party now disgraced and stripped of 
authority 
modrow has agreed to include opposition forces in his cabinet 
until free elections are held on may 6 but the prodemocracy 
groups like new forum democratic awakening and the social 
democrats disagree among themselves how large a role they should 
take on 
the parties would also be taking on partial responsibility for 
the disastrous state of the east german economy and the uncertain 
political situation 
earlier thursday a leading politician dresden mayor wolfgang 
berghofer told his city council that german unification is 
inevitable because east germany never developed a separate national 
identity 
germany was split into communist east and capitalist west after 
adolf hitlers nazi regime was defeated in world war ii 
it is unavoidable that what belongs together will grow 
together said berghofer who quit the communist party on sunday 
the only question is in what time frame and in what manner it 
will occur 
modrow will visit bonn on feb 1314 to meet with west german 
chancellor helmut kohl to discuss the dire economic and political 
problems in east germany kohl chief of staff rudolf seiters 
announced 
on thursday economics minister christa luft told a news 
conference the government has scrapped plans to limit foreign 
ownership of joint ventures to 49 percent a concession to western 
business executives who spurned the earlier conditions 
east germany also will lift all restrictions on competition 
among private industry and crafts people effectively opening the 
national economy to free enterprise government spokesman wolfgang 
meyer announced 
the steps embracing capitalism illustrate the heightened fears 
among east german leaders that the nation is headed toward economic 
collapse 
statistics this week showed a sharp drop in production and ms 
luft confirmed that about 2000 east germans are fleeing the nation 
each day 
hundreds of thousands of east germans fled last year growing 
street protests toppled the hardline regime of erich honecker 
new communist leaders opened the berlin wall and promised free 
elections to placate the masses but the exodus west apparently has 
not been halted 
seiters said more than 42500 east germans had moved to west 
germany since jan 1 
the exodus has robbed east germany of vital labor strength and 
undermines economic recovery efforts 
communist officials tried unsuccessfully beginning last fall to 
adopt an economy combining socialism and capitalism but pressure 
for more radical change forced the communists to yield to western 
business demands 
majority foreign ownership of east german businesses will be 
allowed for any small and mediumsize firms and for any projects 
in the publics economic interest ms luft said 
ms luft suggested that the condition of public economic 
interest would be loosely defined to ensure interest among 
western investors 
she also confirmed that east germany has accepted west german 
promises of 35 billion in aid an offer initially rejected on 
the grounds that bonns demands for a freer east german market were 
unacceptable 
the conditions involved changing the east german economy such 
as competition among enterprises and favorable tax laws and other 
incentives for foreign investors 
</TEXT>
