three defense analysts thursday urged the bush 
administration and congress to cancel or defer a dozen weapon or 
other military projects they said the united states no longer needs 
in a time of a diminishing soviet threat and budget constraints 
if we arent careful about our hardware choices today we 
wont have the funds to buy them efficiently or to spend on other 
defense needs gordon adams director of the defense budget 
project told reporters at a news conference 
adams was joined by dr william kaufmann and lawrence korb of 
the brookings institution 
the defense budget project is somewhat left of the center of the 
political spectrum brookings is closer to the center but its 
staff frequently advocates liberal positions kaufmann a retired 
professor at massachusetts institute of technology and often a 
consultant to the pentagon is coauthor of an annual report on the 
defense budget that in recent years has advocated less spending 
korb served as an assistant secretary of defense in the reagan 
administration 
the experts said buying the dozen weapons will cost 124 billion 
in current dollars from 1991 to 1995 and 342 billion by the time 
they are completed 
the defense budget that president bush will unveil monday for 
the fiscal year beginning oct 1 the 1991 year will be about 303 
billion 
among the weapons the three analysts slated for deferral are the 
amraam missile the army tactical missile the a12 advanced 
tactical aircraft the advanced tactical fighter the c17 
transport aircraft the lhx helicopter and the seawolf attack 
submarine 
the urged cancellation of the antisatellite missile the b2 
stealth bomber the railcar mobile basing of the mx missile the 
sramt tactical shortrange attack missile and the milstar 
satellite system 
a revolution in military affairs could be in the making at 
least in part because of the economic distress in the soviet union 
and the changes in the soviet leadership kaufmann said but 
one thing is clear the revolution will not progress much further 
without initiatives from and cooperation by the united states 
