agriculture secretary clayton yeutter and epa 
chief william k reilly expressed differences thursday on the need 
to regulate pesticides found in ground water yeutter saying no 
reilly saying yes 
i dont think farmers need to be regulated in this area 
yeutter told the senate agriculture committee which is beginning 
work on the 1990 farm bill 
yeuetter who was taken to task by the committee chairman for 
alleged antienvironmentqal remarks later backtracked a bit to 
concede that some regulation is inevitable 
farmers are not deliberately damaging the environment and have 
never done so he said they are sometimes innocent victims of 
environmental degradation but they are not the culprits 
he said farmers need instead to be informed stimulated and 
encouraged to engage in sound practices 
environmental protection agency administrator reilly said at the 
same hearing that the agency is evaluating old and new pesticides 
for ground water contamination potential 
based on these and other data the agency will decide whether 
to use nationally applicable restrictions to regulate pesticides 
posing widespread national concerns he said examples would 
include allowing only licensed applicators to use the chemicals or 
imposing regional bans on use 
he said his department is developing a ground water pollution 
control strategy that would include pesticide regulations 
the proposed strategy calls for states to develop management 
plans based on local conditions and needs 
he gave as one example a proposed decision on aldicarb under 
which the pesticide could be used only if states operate pesticide 
management plans for it 
but the proposal also includes national restrictions that would 
ban use within 300 feet of wells restriction of use to qualified 
applicators and monitoring requirements 
reilly whose agency regulates pesticides but not fertilizers 
said his agency must closely coordinate with the agriculture 
department 
we understand and are sensitive to the many objectives which 
the farm bill must achieve and that environmental protection is 
only one of these reilly said 
although epa is concerned about growing ground water 
contamination by nitrate compounds from fertilizer and animal 
wastes the options available to farmers are generally limited to 
reducing use or changing basic farming practices to reduce the 
likelihood of contamination he said 
the hearing heated up briefly when committee chairman patrick 
leahy dvt rapped yeutter for remarks critical of 
environmentalists 
it is wrong to claim that environmentalists are forcing 
