<TEXT>
parliament on thursday passed a law 
reining in the once allpowerful security services as the result of 
a national scandal involving illegal spying by secret police on 
opposition parties 
among the scores of people being spied on were some members of 
parliament the new law spells out that covert intelligence 
gathering is allowed only when the security of the nation the 
sovereignty of the country and its constitutional order are 
endangered by secret activities 
as further supervision interior minister state secretary zoltan 
gal and justice minister kalman kulcsar were made responsible for 
intelligence operations 
the measure also changed the name of the main intelligence 
agency from the state security service to national security service 
gal said the law was meant to signal that the secret service 
organs no longer serve the state organization but have as their 
primary aim the security of the entire nation and constitutional 
order 
the bill became law by a vote of 2790 with 14 absentions 
gal told parliament in introducing the bill wednesday that 
intelligence agencies underwent little supervision in the past when 
hungary was a oneparty communist state 
he said a permanent and comprehensive bill governing the 
activities of the security services will be presented in parliament 
next month 
the political spying scandal broke on jan 5 when 
representatives of two opposition organizations handed reporters 
secret documents leaked to them by a member of the secret police 
secret police targets for spying included opposition parties and 
personalities writers and religious figures according to the 
documents 
chief public prosecutor karoly szijarto revealed wednesday the 
illegal eavesdropping was even more widespread than originally 
thought 
he told the legislature the internal security department even 
spied on the socialist party its predecessor the socialist 
workers communist party and other communist or leftist 
organizations the investigation is still under way 
interior minister istvan horvath resigned tuesday though he 
claimed to have had no knowledge of such practices he told 
legislators that in a democracy that is the custom 
hungary formally became a multiparty state oct 23 the first 
free elections here since 1948 are scheduled for march 25 
despite its assertion that it was not involved the scandal is 
believed to have hurt the chances of the socialist party at the 
polls 
