<TEXT>
the rum creek valley was quiet thursday 
after three days of confrontation as members of the united mine 
workers union stepped aside and allowed nonunion trucks to enter a 
coal processing plant 
five pickets had been arrested in the three days of battles with 
nonunion workers and federal marshals outside the rum creek coal 
sales inc plant where the union has been on strike for six months 
four company truck drivers also have been arrested 
i think the union leadership is looking at the situation 
said jesse south a chief deputy us marshal i dont know of 
any plans they may have 
the union is under federal court order to refrain from blocking 
the private road leading to the plant and limit the number of 
pickets at the site to 15 
we want to maintain the peace and try to keep the violence 
down said roger nelson a umw strike organizer if i can clear 
the men out to meet the conditions of the judges order we can 
avoid having a repeat of yesterday 
three pickets were arrested wednesday two for assaulting a 
federal officer 
we didnt have violence until yesterday when the marshals came 
down here and started shoving people around nelson said these 
people are frustrated with the way things are being handled thats 
why we had the violence 
by coincidence thursdays calm came on the 100th anniversary of 
the umws founding 
miners picketing the rum creek plant have blocked the road with 
cars and trucks on monday and tuesday company coal trucks with 
steel plates protecting their radiators plowed the vehicles out of 
the way on wednesday federal marshals had them towed away 
about two dozen miners struck rum creek in midaugust after rum 
creek hired a nonunion contractor to run its plant in southern 
west virginia before then unionized employees had worked the 
plant where coal is sorted and prepared for sale 
the umw was formed jan 25 1890 in columbus ohio by the 
merger of two rival coal miners organizations 
last year its resources were strained by a 9month strike 
tentatively settled jan 1 against the pittston coal group inc 
the tentative settlement has not yet been submitted for 
ratification by the rank and file 
umw members staged wildcat strikes last summer to show support 
for striking pittston miners at the height of that action 43000 
miners in 10 states were off their jobs 
on jan 16 in the first fatality linked to labor violence in 
the coal fields since 1985 one union member was killed and two 
others wounded in a west virginia shootout between picketing miners 
and gunmen 
the slaying was unrelated to the pittston strike or the actions 
at rum creek 
