<TEXT>
cocaine traffickers operating in the 
hinterlands of bolivia are loosening ties to the powerful but 
besieged colombian cartels looking upon them now as bad business 
partners antinarcotics officials say 
since late august when the colombian government declared its 
antidrug war the colombian cartels have often failed to show up 
for deals or make promised payments for wholesale purchases from 
the bolivians the officials say 
they are not paying up gen lucio anez commander of 
bolivias 1040man antinarcotics police force told in an 
interview here theyve got debts in arrears 
the bolivians are doing more refining and smuggling on their 
own anez and other officials said 
the colombian cartels traditionally have bought up most of 
bolivias often crudely processed cocaine it was shipped to cartel 
laboratories for refining into pure cocaine chlorhydrate and 
smuggled to the united states and other wealthy user countries 
bolivia a cocagrowing country supplies an estimated onethird of 
the worlds cocaine 
santa cruz a tropical city 355 miles east of la paz is a 
center for trafficking and a frequent calling point for colombian 
wholesale buyers 
with the buyers now less dependable the bolivians evidently are 
doing more refining on their own 
there is an increase in processing anez said were 
seizing more refined drug 
according to statistics prepared by the us embassy in bolivia 
2288 pounds of refined cocaine hydrochloride were seized in 1989 
compared to just 453 pounds the previous year seizures of 
lessrefined cocaine base dropped from 2950 pounds to 2013 pounds 
anez said his forces also had detected more bolivian cocaine 
moving through alternate smuggling channels 
the routes have shifted a little toward brazil and argentina 
in that order he said 
im not trying to say that theyve stopped shipping to 
colombia which remains the principal partner 
a us antinarcotics official working in bolivia who spoke on 
condition that he not be identified said his office also had 
received information that the colombians were having trouble making 
payments 
business has been disrupted he said 
he added that he was not sure the increased processing in 
bolivia was directly tied to the drug war in colombia he said it 
might be a result of increased consumption of cocaine in europe a 
market that bolivia supplies 
however he expressed the belief that the disruption in 
colombian operations clearly was stinging bolivian coca farmers 
the price for 100 pounds of coca leaf had slumped from about 85 in 
august to as low as about 20 in december he said 
the price drop gave a dramatic boost to a program to get coca 
farmers to switch to other crops in december a record 1303 acres 
of coca were voluntarily destroyed according to the us embassy 
nonetheless the total number of acres dedicated to coca farming 
increased from 84000 in 1985 to 130000 last year coca farming is 
legal in bolivia but processing it is not the coca leaf has been 
chewed somewhat like tobacco by the bolivian indians for 
centuries 
the united states is focusing more of its military police and 
economic aid on cracking down on processors it plans to help the 
bolivian government build a new base where us military and 
police trainers will be stationed in the tropical lowland region 
called the beni where scores of clandestine labs and air strips 
are operating 
the beni base would be a launching point for raids on the labs 
using 12 huey helicopters on loan from the us military 
</TEXT>
