<TEXT>
scientists have isolated natural soil 
bacteria that can detoxify cancercausing vinyl chloride and 
related pollutants 
our work should lead to practical biological methods for 
cleansing the environment of these toxic chemicals in the near 
future said charles castro a chemist at the university of 
california riverside 
vinyl chloride which the environmental protection agency says 
causes cancer is used for making polyvinyl chloride pipes and 
insulation pvc which isnt considered carcinogenic also is used 
in floor tiles and upholstery 
vinyl chloride and other related chemicals called organic 
halides including funguskilling edb and dbcp reach the 
environment as pesticides or manufacturing byproducts edb and dbcp 
have been found to pollute groundwater in some areas 
the bacteria isolated by castro produce enzymes that break 
chemical bonds responsible for the toxicity of vinyl chloride and 
other organic halides the breakdown products further decompose to 
create nontoxic substances such as carbon dioxide simple alcohols 
and organic acids the university said 
castro said his research is aimed at making it commercially 
possible to use the bacteria to detoxify the pollutants he said 
research first must show exactly how and how quickly the process 
works 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
infected inflamed sinuses can masquerade 
as a dental problem by causing a toothache in the upper molars 
says an association of ear nose and throat doctors 
patients should be suspicious that they have sinusitis and not 
dental problems if their pain is combined with nasal discharge or 
stuffiness and if the tenderness is localized in the upper jaw 
area said dr david w kennedy of the american academy of 
otolaryngologyhead and neck surgery 
moira dewilde the groups spokeswoman said the academy decided 
to publicize the problem after a staff member rushed to her dentist 
in acute pain only to find the problem was with her sinuses not 
her teeth 
the maxillary sinus cavity above the upper jaw has membranes 
that can be inflamed and swollen by infection causing pain and 
tenderness in the upper jaw and teeth the condition acute 
sinusitis usually happens after a cold flu or allergy attack 
causes swelling of membranes in the nose the swelling blocks tiny 
openings from the sinuses to the nose allowing mucus to build up 
in the sinuses and causing a feeling of pressure 
dental xrays may not reveal sinusitis which can be treated 
with antibiotics to fight the bacterial infection and with 
decongestants to reduce swelling and help the sinus drain 
recurrent or persistent sinus infections sometimes require surgery 
</TEXT>
