<DOCNO> AP900125-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the energy department is proposing holding its 
nuclear weapons contractors liable for environmental fines and 
other costs resulting from their own negligence 
the proposal announced wednesday by energy secretary james d 
watkins marks the departments most substantial effort to improve 
work at the weapons plants which are plagued by mismanagement 
safety lapses and environmental problems 
this proposal reflects my goal of safeguarding the public and 
protecting the environment watkins said in a statement 
the 17 major weapons production plants and research laboratories 
are owned by the department but operated under longterm contracts 
by private companies since the start of nuclear arms production in 
the 1940s the plant operators have enjoyed virtually complete 
protection from financial liability for their mistakes 
federal auditors last year reported that the energy department 
had paid hundreds of thousands of dollars in environmental fines 
incurred by weapons contractors plus related legal costs that 
totaled about twice as much as the fines 
under the new system contractors would have to pay fines they 
could reasonably have avoided plus legal costs they also would be 
charged for expenses resulting from damage to government property 
although not in all cases 
the department is expected to announce soon a related proposal 
for increasing the amount of bonus money that the contractors can 
earn for excellent performance that would partly offset the 
increased financial liability 
the watkins proposal is subject to change based on comments 
received during a 30day public comment period 
reaction on capitol hill was mixed 
rep ron wyden dore who sponsored legislation last year to 
increase the weapons contractors liability for environmental 
violations said in an interview wednesday that he was not 
satisfied that watkins proposal was tough enough 
it is just full of potential loopholes and i think dangerous 
hedging wyden said he noted as an example a provision that 
would set a ceiling on the amount of damages for which the 
contractors would be liable 
rep david skaggs dcolo whose district includes the rocky 
flats weapons plant issued a statement calling the proposal a 
real victory for common sense he said it offered new hope for 
improving the contractors performance 
now their own money will be at stake and thats a strong 
incentive for contractors to do the job right he said 
steven wakefield the departments general counsel said the 
weapons contractors had been briefed on the outlines of the 
proposal he said some didnt like certain provisions of the plan 
but that none had threatened to quit 
</TEXT>
