<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration says a 
house report recommending a criminal probe into the firings of 
chicago airtraffic controllers was seriously flawed and 
repeated allegations already resolved by the courts 
the faas comments contained in a document filed with a federal 
workers board are the agencys first formal response since 
members of congress accused officials of lying and doctoring time 
sheets to justify the 1981 firings 
many of the reports findings are premised upon conjecture 
theory or speculation the faa said referring to a report 
released by a house public works and transportation subcommittee in 
september 
the report does not contain new evidence regarding the 
reliability of the timekeeping records and its conclusions are 
seriously flawed the agency said in the document which was 
obtained wednesday 
lawmakers spent three years investigating how faa officials at 
the chicago air route traffic control center in aurora ill 
prepared to defend the firings before the merit systems protection 
board 
in their report lawmakers concluded that attendance records 
were in such poor condition that officials decided to create 
documents to bolster the case against controllers who joined a 
nationwide strike 
the report also said faa officials may have committed perjury 
during appearances before the merit board which considers appeals 
from fired federal workers 
armed with the subcommittees report attorneys for the 
controllers are now asking the board to overturn the firings 
but the faa cites several reasons why the board should not 
reopen the case 
the allegations are not new the agency said the board in 1985 
and a federal appeals court in 1987 upheld the dismissals after 
considering similar complaints about time sheets 
the board cannot reopen a case that has been decided in court 
the subcommittee made errors and its report should not be 
considered 
the report not only ignored significant evidence and sworn 
testimony but revealed a significant misunderstanding as to the 
procedures which were used in the removal process the faa 
said 
faa officials acknowledged that some records had been amended 
but maintained the changes were made to ensure accuracy not to 
cheat controllers 
there was no scheme to alter and manufacture evidence which 
did not exist at the time of the strike and which was not prepared 
in the ordinary course of business the faa said 
