<TEXT>
rising interest rates have made japans government 
bonds the most attractive paper on earth at the moment but 
forecasts of a mass exodus of funds from us investments may be 
overblown some experts say 
world markets were unnerved this week when a us offering of 
bonds to finance the savings and loan bailout did not attract the 
usual active interest among the japanese 
that incited fears in the united states because the japanese 
have been eager buyers of us government securities over the last 
several years helping to finance the federal budget deficit and 
hold down interest rates 
one broker joan anway of wi carrs tokyo office proclaimed 
japanese bonds the worlds most attractive but others say the 
factors adding to their allure could be temporary 
us analysts pinned the rise in japanese interest rates to 
inflation fears in japan where the rate more than doubled last 
year to 25 percent and where workers are seeking wage increases of 
6 perent 
for japanese investors the ability to obtain a high return 
without risk is bound to be remarkably attractive said seiichi 
kaneko manager of research in the international asset management 
division of asahi mutual life 
the yield on benchmark 10year japanese government bonds was 
quoted at 657 percent thursday compared to about 840 percent for 
a similar us treasury issue the japanese bond is up from about 
55 percent at the start of the year 
although the gap between the rates offered on us and japanese 
securities is definitely narrowing kaneko predicted there would 
not be any massive exodus of money from the us over the course 
of the year 
he said stock portfolio managers may liquidate some us 
holdings to take profits and offset recent losses in the tokyo 
stock market but after the new japanese fiscal year begins april 
1 kaneko expects managers to reinvest in the united states 
an indication of the extent to which japanese investors are 
fleeing the united states will come from the us treasury 
departments next refunding auction in early february 
kozo nogami manager of international securities investment for 
