<TEXT>
the race to develop highdefinition television 
heated up thursday with the announcement that the us divisions of 
two european electronics giants have joined nbctv to research 
advanced tv systems 
philips consumer electronics co said it will join an existing 
research venture of thomson consumer electronics inc and nbc 
philips is part of nv philips of the netherlands while thomson is 
the us division of thomson sa of france 
the venture faces stiff competition from research efforts under 
way in japan and europe into highdefinition television which 
promises picture quality as crisp as photographs and crystalclear 
sound 
in addition zenith electronics corp the last major tv 
manufacturer in the united states has joined american telephone amp 
telegraph co to develop a hdtv system 
the new threeway alliance of philips thomson and nbc drew 
praise from several industry observers 
i think its a fairly wise competitive decision said pat 
hill hubbard a vice president of the american electronics 
association research is very costly in this field 
laura j lederman an analyst with the chicago investment firm 
duff amp phelps inc said the combination of manufacturers and 
broadcasters was critical 
if you have companies that build a set but you dont have 
broadcasters youre missing some of the pieces she said 
together philips and thomson control almost 40 percent of the 
us televisionset market philips makes the magnavox sylvania 
philco and philips brands while thomson owns the former general 
electric and rca lines 
nbc which is owned by general electric co has been 
cooperating with thomson for several years at the david sarnoff 
research center in princeton nj to develop advanced television 
systems 
nbc and thomson are working on a system called advanced 
compatible tv which would provide an improved picture on new 
widescreen tv sets while allowing continued use of conventional 
sets 
advanced compatible tv would require only minor lowcost 
adjustments to equipment at local tv stations thomson and nbc said 
philips on thursday endorsed the advanced compatible tv system 
we want us consumers to have access to advanced tv services 
as quickly as possible j peter bingham vice president of 
technology for philips consumer electronics said at a news 
conference at nbcs headquarters 
philips has been working on its own improvedtv systems in this 
country and said it would merge its efforts with those of nbc and 
thomson 
the consortium which invited other companies to join its 
effort said it hoped to have the advanced tv system operating and 
the sets on sale by 1993 the companies said they expected the sets 
would sell for 500 to 1000 
at the same time the consortium said it will pursue a true 
highdefinition tv system which would provide even sharper 
pictures 
the hdtv system being considered would require a reallocation of 
broadcasting signals by the federal communications commission since 
it would use the blank channels that now separate the channels in 
use in any one area 
the system would transmit an hdtv signal on one channel and a 
conventional signal on a second channel to meet an fcc requirement 
than any hdtv system not make conventional sets obsolete 
ms hubbard of the american electronics association said the 
trade group was pleased that the consortium joins three companies 
who are trying to keep the technology base in this country 
asked whether zenith would consider joining the consortium 
spokesman john taylor said were very pleased with the progress 
that we have been making in the development of our own system 
each of the groups developing highdefinition tv systems in the 
united states hopes its version is picked as the nations standard 
by the fcc which is scheduled to start testing proposed systems 
soon 
in addition to their us venture thomson and philips are 
involved in a european governmentindustry consortium to develop 
hdtv there 
japan has been researching hdtv for more than two decades and is 
considered by many experts to have the lead 
some experts say the nation that wins the hdtv race will have an 
enormous advantage in the broader electronics market 
